<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police tackling theft of heavy equipment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MERIDEN, Conn. (AP) -- It may seem hard for a thief to hide a
two-ton truck or piece of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But authorities say the theft of heavy equipment has become a
lucrative trade, and some police officers don't know where to look
--or how.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide last year, police reported 16,500 missing pieces of
construction equipment valued at about $567 million. Most of the
equipment sold for 10 to 20 percent of actual value within 300
miles of where it was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Few pieces have been recovered and law enforcement officers
concede they have not paid enough attention to an expensive
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all get excited looking for a stolen Toyota worth $8,000,''
said Paul Morgan, a sheriff in Charles County, Md. ''But few of us
know how to find a stolen dump truck that might be worth $60,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, who travels nationwide to teach police officers and
vehicle inspectors how to spot stolen heavy equipment, recently led
a class at the Connecticut Police Academy. About 50 municipal
officers, state vehicle inspectors and state troopers learned about
trucks and the documents the drivers are required to carry.
</P>
<P>
   They also were shown as many as 18 places on construction
equipment where manufacturers put hard-to-find, and
harder-to-erase, ID numbers. Morgan told officers to carry a can of
brake cleaner and lots of rags so they can wipe away grease or
spray-paint that thieves sometimes use to conceal the more visible
ID numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The course, the first of a series, was sponsored by the state
police vehicle-theft task force, which recently broke up a ring
that may have stolen as much as $1 million worth of construction
equipment from the shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stolen construction equipment is a big problem that we're
targeting. It's bad along the I-95 corridor,'' said task force
commander Lt. John Duley. ''Our unit had to learn how to look for
it. Now we hope these classes will increase enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Garry Jones, an inspector with the state Department of Motor
Vehicles anti-theft unit, said he had always just checked
tractor-trailers to ensure they are registered.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now, I'll know how to check the bulldozers, backhoes and other
stuff that's on the trailers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said the equipment is often sold at bargain prices to
struggling contractors who don't question the cheap prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had one case of a stolen skidder worth $18,000 sold for
$1,600,'' Morgan said. ''The guy who bought it had to know it was
stolen. He told us he'd bought it from some guy he met on a job and
he only knew him as 'JimBob.'''
</P>
<P>
   The skidder was stolen from a dealer's lot by thieves who pulled
up with a tractor, hooked up a trailer and drove away, Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent statistics show that police throughout the
country recover just 16 percent of stolen heavy equipment --compared
with 60 percent of all stolen cars, Morgan said. That's often
because road patrol officers don't know what to look for.
</P>
<P>
   ''Heavy equipment is confusing. They're not like cars. They
don't require titles, registrations or licenses,'' he said. ''You
could stop a tractor-trailer that is properly registered and have
no clue that the $70,000 loader it's hauling is stolen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
