<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coast Guard cuts Delaware River patrols, blames tight budget  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The U.S. Coast Guard has ceased routine
patrols of the Delaware River between Trenton and the Delaware Bay
to cut costs, though officials said it will stay on call for
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reason we're reducing operations is to protect our
emergency search-and-rescue capability and for those surge
operations -- hurricanes, floods -- the public-safety issues we have
to keep number one,'' Coast Guard Cmdr. Pat Philbin said.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin, aide to Coast Guard Commandant Adm. James M. Loy, spoke
Friday from Washington, D.C., where the agency is seeking $71
million more than is in the current $4 billion budget in order to
restore services such as river patrols across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel costs have increased sharply since the Coast Guard budget
was approved last year, but Philbin said the rising fuel costs are
''only about 10 percent of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The larger problems are rising medical costs, pay, and
personnel issues,'' he said. ''More than two-thirds of every dollar
is spent on personnel costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those costs are fixed, hurting the agency's ability to
quickly cope with a budget pinch, Philbin added.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really difficult to save a lot real fast, because a lot
of our money is wrapped up in personnel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard eliminated its daily warm-weather two-boat
patrol of the Delaware River between Trenton and the Delaware Bay
in early May.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard patrolled the river Friday as part of Maritime
Day, which had been scheduled before the cutback. The event
celebrating commerce on the river includes a tugboat parade, rowing
races and a regatta.
</P>
<P>
   At the wheel of the 41-foot patrol boat, Petty Officer Peter
Mallett was uncertain whether the absence of patrols would affect
boating safety.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard would still respond to any emergency on the
river, such as the recent collapse of Pier 34, Mallett said.
</P>
<P>
   And he noted that other agencies, such as the Philadelphia
Police Department, New Jersey State Police, Pennsylvania Fish and
Boat Commission and Delaware Department of Natural Resources
regularly patrol the river.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sgt. Edward Oleyn, aboard a 23-foot outboard from the
Philadelphia Police marine unit, pointed out, ''The more people you
have, the better protection you have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-04-00 1322 </TRAILER>
