<HEADLINE> Wagner Family Clash Over Festival  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The Festspielhaus theater was built by Richard
Wagner in the 1870s as the ideal setting for his epic operas, and
thousands of the cultural elite flock to the Bavarian town of
Bayreuth each year for its always sold-out festival to see the
Valkyries fly in their natural setting.
</P>
<P>
   As the world-famous Bayreuth festival heads into its 89th year
under the leadership of Wagner's descendants, a dispute is brewing
within the family worthy of a dramatization by their famous
forefather.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's great-granddaughter, a leading candidate to become
festival director at a vote Monday, has made the dramatic
suggestion to move parts of the festival out of the theater into
the open air -- and even to include more Beethoven and less Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   But her 80-year-old uncle, who has headed the festival for 50
years, vows to prevent her from getting the post and thwart the
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure for the festival to change isn't just coming from
within the family.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Germany's Culture Minister Michael Naumann was booed
at the festival over plans to trim its federal subsidies, and
demonstrators protested his invitation to the opening performance.
</P>
<P>
   As an answer to drying-up government money, Nike Wagner has
proposed staging festival activities outside the Festspielhaus in
Bayreuth's main square that would be financed with corporate
joint-ventures.
</P>
<P>
   And in a homage to composers who both inspired Wagner and were
inspired by him, she suggests that more non-Wagner works be
included in the two-week program staged each summer -- such as
Beethoven, but also modern composers and works yet to be written.
</P>
<P>
   ''Wagner's drama thrives on risk, not routine,'' Nike Wagner
wrote in a passionate article in Germany's leading Frankfurter
Allgemeine Zeitung newspaper with her co-candidate for artistic
director, Elmar Weingarten, director of the Berlin Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it does not seriously concern itself with the situation of
music theater and art today, the festival will risk becoming
repetitive, always returning to its old-fashioned roots.''
</P>
<P>
   But the festival's patriarch, Wolfgang Wagner, grandson of
Richard Wagner, has vowed to stay on in his lifetime post if such
proposals win the day -- insisting that his second wife and longtime
assistant, Gudrun Wagner, is the only one who can succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   The decision of who heads the festival reaches to the highest
levels of German government: Federal, state and local officials all
vote on the 24-member festival board that includes four members of
the Wagner family.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner is revered by opera lovers but also has a special place
of honor and controversy in Germany, where his rousing arpeggios
ornamenting stories of mythical Germanic heroes were a favorite of
Adolf Hitler. The festival continued under the Nazi regime, and
Wolfgang's mother and then-director, Winifred, was a glowing
admirer of Hitler -- whom the family gave the fond nickname
''Wolf.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang Wagner has publicly blasted his niece, Nike, and has
dismissed his daughter, Eva Wagner-Pasquier -- who had been viewed
as his eminent successor -- as unfit for the post. He says his wife,
whom he wants in the spot, has been the victim of a smear campaign.
At three women are in their mid-50s.
</P>
<P>
   Nike Wagner's plans for the festival are ''unrealistic'' and
''contrary'' to the idea for the festival, Wolfgang Wagner said in
this week's Der Spiegel newsmagazine.
</P>
<P>
   ''At no time have I made it unclear that I will continue to
fulfill my contract as long as by my assessment an unqualified
successor is named,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang Wagner isn't in much of a hurry to leave, anyway. He
has already pledged to stay on as director at least until 2001,
when a celebration of his 50th year heading the festival is
planned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 1332 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000604.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firefighter's device links those deep in blaze  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   VERNON, Conn. (AP) -- John Bieback knows how the heat, smoke and
muffling breathing masks can make the distance between firefighters
standing feet apart seem like miles.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've stood at funerals and said, 'There's got to be a better
way,'' said Biebeck, a member of Manchester's fire department.
</P>
<P>
   Bieback, 53, has spent more than a decade and $70,000 of his own
money to develop TeamTalk, a device that allows firefighters to
communicate in burning buildings. The palm-size, wireless radio
clips onto a firefighter's breathing mask and is activated by
pressing a button on the side.
</P>
<P>
   The device, being developed by Bieback's Vernon-based Safety
Tech Industries Inc., is not expected to hit the market until later
this year. But it has already gotten positive reviews from
firefighters from Michigan to Waterbury who have tested it.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those firefighters ended up investing in the product,
including Waterbury Fire Capt. Michael Farrell.
</P>
<P>
   ''They thought this thing out. That's the beauty of it,'' he
said. ''They didn't rush this into production. You can tell this
equipment is designed and built by firemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bieback, who has dabbled in electronics since high school, said
he conceived of the idea after responding to an attic fire in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was yelling through the mask. It was absurd,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An engineering graduate who left the field when he was 35 and
discovered volunteer firefighting, Bieback said the prototype has
gone through many changes at the suggestion of firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are designing it whether they know it or not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Oaks Fire Department in Michigan tried TeamTalk in a
building in which firefighters donned full gear and used fans and
generators to create background noise.
</P>
<P>
   ''It worked well in practice,'' said Royal Oaks, Mich., Fire
Chief Richard Strehlke, who is not one of Safety Tech's investors.
Other devices on the market just amplify the firefighter's voice or
have wires that must be connected to a radio, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, TeamTalk joins a growing arsenal of technology
designed to give fire scene commanders a better feel for how
firefighters fare when they enter burning buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Bieback believes the demand will be great for TeamTalk among the
nation's 32,000 fire departments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anytime you read about the most tragic types of fire, when
there is a loss of life, one of the biggest things in the
investigation is the lack of communication,'' Connecticut State
Fire Administrator Jeff Morrissette said.
</P>
<P>
   The company still has to demonstrate that the device won't cause
a spark when operated and is awaiting final approval from the
Federal Communications Commission, but Bieback does not believe
those are major hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   He and his partner, Peter LaPlaca, are now meeting with venture
capitalists to secure $3 million for production and the national
launch.
</P>
<P>
   The introductory price will be $450 a unit, which will not yield
much of a profit, LaPlaca said. The price is expected to go up by
about $100 a unit the next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-04-00 1335 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000604.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eccentric engineer goes from Ellis Island to guiding G.E., America  </HEADLINE>
By JUDY PATRICK
The Daily Gazette
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) -- Charles Proteus Steinmetz stood less
than 5 feet tall, an odd-looking hunchbacked man U.S. immigration
officials nearly sent back to Prussia when he arrived at Ellis
Island in 1889. But within four years, Steinmetz had become chief
consultant engineer at General Electric Co., eventually working out
of its showcase Schenectady plant.
</P>
<P>
   He was an engaging, eccentric personality full of ideas and
determination; he kept a menagerie -- an owl, raccoon, alligator,
cranes and a monkey -- in his back yard and operated his own home
greenhouse and laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   By the turn of the century, he had persuaded GE to take the
major financial risk of establishing a laboratory dedicated to
industrial research. That laboratory, today known as General
Electric Corporate Research and Development in the Schenectady
suburb of Niskayuna, this year is marking its 100th anniversary,
paying tribute to Steinmetz's founding vision and the evolution of
the laboratory through the decades that followed.
</P>
<P>
   A century has changed many things. When Steinmetz began lobbying
for creation of the research laboratory, General Electric was a
young, pioneering company in the fledgling electrical industry. It
specialized in the manufacture of electric streetcars, industrial
motors and light bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   Today, GE is one of the world's biggest industrial
conglomerates, with a market value of more than $518 billion and
annual sales of $117.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While all sorts of factors have shaped GE, the research
laboratory has provided many of the ideas on which that growth has
been based. Over the years, its researchers have won two Nobel
Prizes and secured more than 60,000 patents. Their work has
stretched from better light bulbs to plastics, man-made diamonds,
nuclear energy and medical imaging.
</P>
<P>
   When Steinmetz began lobbying for creation of a research lab,
General Electric already had scientists working in laboratories.
But the research laboratory was something new, something far
different than company founder Thomas Edison's famed ''invention
factory'' in Menlo Park, N.J..
</P>
<P>
   ''This was the first industrial laboratory dedicated to pure
research as opposed to coming up with inventions,'' said George
Wise, a retired GE scientist who has studied the center's history.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Edison's lab, the scientists had to keep coming up with
something useful.'' Steinmetz's vision was for a research lab where
scientists were sheltered from the pressures of the production line
and business department.
</P>
<P>
   But from the beginning, the laboratory was steeped in a
pragmatism that began, at its founding, with the light bulb. Screw
in one of Thomas Edison's old light bulbs today and -- 100 years
later -- there's a chance it may still light up.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum, a lot of the old light bulbs
fizzled out after only a few hours of use. The inconsistency rested
with the filament, the slender thread of material that becomes
incandescent as electricity passes through.
</P>
<P>
   Edison's original light bulbs used carbon, which, while
inexpensive, proved to be a fickle medium for filament. In some
cases, it seemed to burn forever. In others, it burned out within
hours. Carbon filament was also difficult and expensive to
manufacture, involving hammering and shaping individual pieces of
carbon and baking them in a furnace. Despite its shortcomings, the
carbon filament light bulb was brighter and safer than the
gaslights of the past.
</P>
<P>
   But for Edison's company, the fledgling General Electric Co.,
the manufacturing inconsistency was a nagging problem.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, research laboratories in Europe were working
on ways to improve the light bulb, using metal filaments in place
of carbon. Steinmetz, aware of those developments, stepped up his
lobbying for a research lab to do similar work.
</P>
<P>
   ''Due to the extreme slowness with which we are moving in this
matter, it appears that the field will be exploited before we start
to do anything therein and we s h a l l b e l e f t b e h i n d,''
Steinmetz wrote in a Sept. 20, 1897, letter to company Vice
President Edwin Rice. For emphasis, he carefully spaced out the
typed letters of the last four words.
</P>
<P>
   Albert P. Davis, a top GE official at the time, made a similar
appeal to Rice, this in a September 1900 letter: ''If someone else
gets ahead of us in this development, we will have to spend large
sums in buying patents or patent rights, whereas if we do the work
ourselves, this necessity will be avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporate officers, led by Rice, were convinced. That fall,
after several years of lobbying, Steinmetz got the approval he
needed from GE's board of directors to set up a company laboratory
devoted to research.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Davis told an interviewer: ''I was never able to
make up my mind whether the first suggestion for the Research
Laboratory came from Steinmetz or from myself. Looking back on it
now in 1933, I see that it may well be that Steinmetz originated
the idea, and that in his efforts to get Mr. Rice and myself to
endorse it, he was astute enough to make each of us separately feel
himself the originator.''
</P>
<P>
   With his approval in hand, Steinmetz went about the business of
setting up shop. Steinmetz asked for $20,000 to buy equipment for
that first lab.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-04-00 1337 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000604.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Drawn to Reclaimed Land  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN SEVAREID
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALONG THE LEBANON-ISRAEL BORDER (AP) -- In villages and wide-open
stretches of hills and valleys that form the Lebanon-Israel
frontier, Lebanese have been drawn to their country's southern edge
to take their first close look at the land they've reclaimed and
the enemy who left.
</P>
<P>
   All traffic seemed to head south in the week after May 24, when
Israel finished withdrawing its troops and ended 22 years operating
in southern Lebanon. Thousands came to the border fence -- the
closest they can get to Israel -- to celebrate, to vent a lifetime
of anger or just to gawk.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mommy! An Israeli, mommy!'' a girl of about 5 cried out,
pointing to an Israeli soldier who peeked out from behind a border
outpost less than 30 feet away that was being pelted by
stone-throwers on the Lebanese side.
</P>
<P>
   Even during the occupation, people rarely saw an Israeli so
close. Israel's allied Lebanese militiamen had patrolled villages,
while Israeli soldiers tended to stay closer to their hilltop
bases, out of sight of guerrillas and civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past week, excitement reigned all along more than 60
miles of border fence -- from the disputed Chebaa farms in the
foothills of Mount Hermon in the east to the Mediterranean Sea in
the west.
</P>
<P>
   But there also were reminders that many in Lebanon don't
consider the liberation complete.
</P>
<P>
   Some visitors to Chebaa left celebrations in the village behind
for a few quiet moments among the goats grazing near a barbed-wire
fence patrolled by Israeli soldiers. Lebanese want Israel's
withdrawal to include the lands on the other side where Chebaa's
residents once farmed.
</P>
<P>
   Borders between Lebanon and Syria in the area known as Chebaa
farms have never been clear, and the farmland is unlikely to be
returned until Syria and Israel make peace. So for now Lebanese
landowners can approach, but not enter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope and wish that all those people who came here and walked
away will have the chance to come back and walk on their land,''
said Ismail Sharifa, 43, who said his family owns land beyond the
locked yellow gate.
</P>
<P>
   Ten miles along the fence to the southwest, across hills dotted
with U.N. checkpoints and blown-up remains of Israeli outposts, a
Hezbollah guerrilla stands as a border guard near the Abbassiyeh
gate, where Lebanese Druse used to cross to work on Israeli farms.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the guerrilla says, no one is allowed within 200 yards of
the gate. ''There is no contact with the enemy except with weapons
and steel,'' he says, refusing to give his name.
</P>
<P>
   Some compromises, however, are required. Checkpoint guards tell
two Druse men they can approach to collect their final pay through
the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Since the pullout, the largest groups by far have gathered at
the Kfar Kila border, 12 miles along the fence west of Abbassiyeh
gate, where vendors set up stands selling date rolls, beans and
corn on the cob.
</P>
<P>
   At times, flag-waving celebrations turned violent. On May 28,
Israeli gunfire wounded at least three people during stone-throwing
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to go inside ... to challenge them,'' Fayad Abbas
Uzayer, a 19-year-old Hezbollah supporter said, his face flushed
with excitement after jumping the fence and drawing warning shots
from the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   There was more stone-throwing at the site on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Six miles south, Amin Ahmed Mataar, 66, and two dozen children,
grandchildren, nieces and nephews chose a quieter stretch of fence.
Climbing a rusted bedspring to the low roof of an abandoned house
five yards from the border, they looked down on Margoliot, Israel --
built near the village Hannin that Mataar fled at age 14 in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mosque was there. I still remember the mosque,'' Mataar
says, pointing past a sign warning of land mines in Arabic, English
and Hebrew and toward a cluster of trees on a low hill a half mile
away.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Mataar, who now lives in Nabatiyeh 12 miles to the
north of where they were standing, told his family stories about
his childhood in Hannin.
</P>
<P>
   ''Down there was my grandfather's house,'' says 13-year-old Ali
Fawzi Mataar, a nephew of the elder Mataar. ''They were sitting in
their house when the Israelis kicked them out and took our land.
... I want to see it when the Zionists leave.''
</P>
<P>
   For many Palestinians in Lebanon, the end of Israeli occupation
allows a look at their homeland but doesn't change the dim
prospects for their return.
</P>
<P>
   At a narrow ledge above Doheira, 30 miles further southwest
along the fence, Palestinians whose families fled or were driven
out at Israel's creation in 1948 greeted relatives who stayed on
the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Without the buffer zone, relatives who'd never met or hadn't
seen each other in 52 years were reaching through barbed wire to
shake hands, share a pot of coffee and catch up on births,
marriages, deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Maher al-Ali's family once lived in Basa, a village six miles
from where he stood that has since become an industrial zone of the
Israeli community of Shlomi.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the 20-year-old said, he had the chance to
vent his views directly to an Israeli in a conversation with a
soldier through the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told him this country is for us, not for him, and he said
this country is for him because his grandfather said it was for
him,'' al-Ali said. ''I told him he was a stranger and what is
taken by force will be returned by force.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
