<HEADLINE> Boris Yeltsin on Political Sidelines  </HEADLINE>
By NICK WADHAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- At state ceremonies in Russia these days, it's
common to see former President Boris Yeltsin standing beside his
successor, Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Yeltsin walks stiffly to his stretch Mercedes
limousine, still decorated with little Russian flags bearing the
presidential emblem and zooms back home to his retreat outside
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   But despite such honors and trappings, the man ceremoniously
referred to as Russia's ''First President'' since he stepped down
on Dec. 31, remains mostly on the political sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is schfile high, said historian Roy
Medvedev, who has written extensively about Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yeltsin wants to show he hasn't left the political scene,''
Medvedev said. ''He doesn't want people to forget about him.''
</P>
<P>
   When 69-year-old Yeltsin resigned unexpectedly last December,
aides and family members said he would set up a political
foundation and travel frequently. He was given an office in the
Kremlin and there was talk that he would use his influence abroad
to negotiate on some diplomatic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin named Putin acting president, giving him a huge
advantage in the presidential elections that Putin won in March.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin makes occasional remarks that indicate he still believes
his sway on Russian politics is high.
</P>
<P>
   ''Under my influence, he will not let us down,'' Yeltsin said of
Putin in January.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin's health apparently hasn't gotten any better since
his days as president, when bouts of pneumonia, an ulcer and heart
problems frequently left him hospitalized. Now he sometimes looks
off-balance and his speech is slow and halting. At other times he
seems fairly well.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has never criticized Yeltsin, saying that the two keep in
touch and that he's occasionally visited the former president to
talk.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin still has authority as a defender of civil freedoms and
reforms, and Putin wants him around to legitimize his own quick
rise to power, said Ekaterina Yegorova, a one-time image consultant
to Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   That was evident at Putin's May 7 inauguration, when the crowd
fidgeted through a meandering Yeltsin speech marked by his
customary long pauses. Yet his presence was a powerful symbol for
Putin, Yegorova said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Putin needs Yeltsin to show he's a man who doesn't forget
history, that he will continue democratic reforms,'' she said.
''That highlights his positive qualities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
