<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan PM Chided for Military Talk  </HEADLINE>
By GARY SCHAEFER
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Days after apologizing for calling Japan a ''divine
nation,'' Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori was criticized again Sunday
for using language associated with the country's militaristic past.
</P>
<P>
   During a campaign speech on Saturday night, Mori referred to
Japan as a ''kokutai'' or ''national polity'' -- a now-archaic term
used in the decades leading up to World War II to connote a
Japanese nation-state ruled by a divine emperor.
</P>
<P>
   Mori, 62, used it while criticizing the Japanese Communist Party
for rejecting the emperor's current constitutional role as a symbol
of the state and for opposing Japan's security treaty with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''Can (such a party) ensure Japan's security and defend the
national polity?'' he said during a speech.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks made front-page headlines in several national
newspapers, and opposition politicians condemned Mori during a
television debate broadcast Sunday on the Asahi network.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a term originally based on the idea of rule by the
emperor,'' said Naoto Kan, a leader of the Democratic Party of
Japan, the country's largest opposition group. ''Why did he use it
specifically?''
</P>
<P>
   Hideyo Fudehisa, chief policy-maker for the Japanese Communist
Party, questioned Mori's leadership credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ''That kind of language may be acceptable from any person of his
age, but it's not acceptable from the prime minister of this
country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Shizuka Kamei, a senior member of Mori's Liberal Democratic
Party, blamed the media for ''twisting'' the prime minister's
words.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was unquestionably talking about the (current) national
system,'' Kamei said.
</P>
<P>
   Mori said in a speech later Sunday that he had made a ''slip of
the tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I was supposed to speak for 30 or 40 minutes and got in
trouble because I ended up talking for more than an hour and made a
slip of the tongue,'' he told an audience in the southwestern city
of Matsuyama.
</P>
<P>
   The government is still reeling from the uproar caused late last
month when Mori called Japan ''a divine nation centered around the
emperor.'' His remarks stirred memories of soldiers marching off to
war in the name of an emperor-god.
</P>
<P>
   Though the prime minister apologized at a news conference on May
26, the controversy has dealt a heavy blow to public support for
his administration just three weeks ahead of national elections.
</P>
<P>
   Several newspaper polls showed Mori's approval ratings tumbling
to 20 percent or lower from about 40 percent when he took office on
April 5.
</P>
<P>
   Last month opposition parties called his ''divine nation''
statement ''unconstitutional'' and demanded he resign.
</P>
<P>
   The emperor was reduced to symbolic status by Japan's 1946
constitution, which provides for the separation of church and
state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 1432 </TRAILER>
