<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Fields Russians' Questions  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID McHUGH
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- President Clinton fielded curious Russians'
questions Sunday about how he made his first dollar, whether he was
tempted to use the police against the media -- and would he mind
being ''first mister'' if his wife Hillary ever becomes president?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared to relax and enjoy himself in the informal
setting of a 25-minute call-in show in the studio of Echo of Moscow
Radio, which followed formal talks at Kremlin with President
Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Russians appeared eager to hear about Clinton's
personal life -- information they rarely get from their own leaders,
including Putin. Hundreds of people had sent in questions hours in
advance by e-mail and by phone.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gave patient, easy answers to questions such as how he
earned his first dollar (cutting lawns) and whether he was
satisfied with daughter Chelsea's progress in college (he is).
</P>
<P>
   He laughed and got a bit red in the face when asked by show host
Aleksei Venediktov ''are you ready to return to the White House as
the spouse of the president, as First Mister?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was proud of Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is
running for Senate from New York. He said his wife had promised to
serve a full term if elected.
</P>
<P>
   After that, ''If she wants to continue in public life, I'll
support her in any way I can,'' said Clinton. Clinton added that he
expects Vice President Gore to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seemed shocked when asked by Venediktov if he'd even
been tempted to crack down on journalists. ''Could you ask the tax
authorities to audit CNN?'' asked Venediktov.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never did that ... That would be illegal,'' Clinton said
emphatically.
</P>
<P>
   The radio station belongs to the Media-MOST group, which was
raided May 11 by ski-masked police investigating allegations the
group's security service was bugging people. MOST head Vladimir
Gusinsky says the company was being punished for critical coverage
of the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   There were no queries about Clinton's relationship with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky, who has received extensive
media attention in Russia, although questions submitted about her
appeared on the station's website.
</P>
<P>
   One listener wanted to know when was the last time Clinton
handled cash. ''About an hour ago,'' said Clinton. ''I'm going to
dinner after I talk to you, so I brought my money with me.''
</P>
<P>
   While the mood was generally positive, some callers betrayed the
suspicion that colors many ordinary Russians' opinions on the
United States and reflect their country's poverty and loss of world
power.
</P>
<P>
   Denis from Samara asked whether Clinton considered Russia a
Third World country. ''No... no!'' said Clinton. ''Russia was badly
hurt by the recent economic crisis'' but wasn't a Third World
country, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the radio interview Sunday, the NTV television station
aired its popular satirical puppet show ''Kukly,'' which showed
Putin, an ex-KGB officer, dream that he recruits Clinton to the
Russian secret services.
</P>
<P>
   Putin tells Clinton that if he doesn't join, the American people
will learn that he avoided the draft and other secrets. Clinton
laughs, telling him America already knows all there is to know
about him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 1511 </TRAILER>
