<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kidnapped Israeli Boy Returns Home  </HEADLINE>
By EYAL WARSHAVSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOD, Israel (AP) -- A 12-year-old Israeli boy who was kept in
horrifying conditions in a cold, wet basement in southern Russia
for nine months and maimed by his kidnappers returned home on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Looking thin and pale, Adi Sharon smiled at relatives waiting
for him at the Ben Gurion Airport as he was carried on a stretcher
to a waiting ambulance. He was taken to Tel-Hashomer hospital,
outside Tel Aviv. He was also met by the minister for immigration
and absorption, Yuli Tamir, foreign ministry officials and a crush
of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   At the hospital, the head of the children's intensive care unit,
Dr. Zohar Barzilai, said Adi was hemorrhaging on the flight from
Moscow and was in a very poor nutritional state. ''He looks
frightened, pale, tired and worried, but he is fully conscious. He
speaks quite freely,'' Barzilai told Channel 2 television.
</P>
<P>
   Adi was in ''moderately serious'' condition, said Alexander
Valerin, head of the Russian Interior Ministry hospital where the
boy was treated after his release, adding that it could take months
for him to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Adi was rescued Friday in the town of Penza, about 350 miles
southeast of the Russian capital of Moscow. He had come to Moscow
in August to visit his father, who was there on business, when he
was kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's father, Yosef, was also captured, but freed a few days
later on condition that he pay $8 million for his son's release.
</P>
<P>
   Adi was held in a narrow, sometimes cold and wet pit in a
basement, his feet shackled, Russian and Israeli news reports said.
Kidnappers cut off parts of the little fingers on both his hands
and sent them to his father as demands for ransom payments.
</P>
<P>
   Video footage broadcast on Russian television Friday showed
police pulling the trembling boy out of a basement filled with
trash. Adi's feet were wrapped in plastic bags and rags, and
Israeli news reports said gangrene had set in.
</P>
<P>
   Adi was severely emaciated, doctors said. He could not stand or
walk when he was taken out of the basement, according to Russian
news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak praised Russian President
Vladimir Putin for his role in the rescue, saying Adi's release
showed that the two countries are on the same wavelength when it
comes to fighting terrorism ''with determination and seriousness
and without wavering.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why it took the Russian authorities so long to rescue the
boy, Russian Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo -- who accompanied
the boy from Moscow to Israel -- said Russia is much bigger than
Israel and a large number of people were involved in the
''conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't immediately clear whether any ransom was paid.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen people have been detained in Moscow, Penza and the
Caucasus Mountains republic of Ingushetia -- next to the breakaway
region of Chechnya -- on suspicion of being involved in the
kidnapping, Russian news reports said. The reports said several of
the suspects were from Chechnya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 1518 </TRAILER>
