<HEADLINE> Devil Rays 15, Mets 5  </HEADLINE>
By HAL BOCK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Pitching in the American League, Esteban Yan
never had to swing a bat before. After Sunday, he could get to like
this National League custom.
</P>
<P>
   Yan hit the first pitch of his first professional at-bat for a
home run and the Tampa Bay Devil Rays routed the New York Mets
15-5.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Martinez, who also had never homered before in the majors,
connected on the pitch before Yan hit his homer. Bubba Trammell
added his third pinch-hit home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Fred McGriff got his 2,000th career hit and Gerald Williams had
three doubles and four RBIs for the Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was 10 years old in the Dominican Republic, I played
catcher and outfield, but I never had a professional at-bat, not
even in the minors,'' Yan said. ''I hit the ball well and I was
hoping it would be two bases, so I was running hard. (Coach) Jose
Cardenal said it's going, so then I slowed down. It's going, I
might as well taken my time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yan's homer was a stunner, but not to manager Larry Rothschild.
</P>
<P>
   ''I pitched batting practice to him in the minors,'' he said.
''I thought he had a chance the way he could swing. I didn't expect
that, obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the victim, loser Bobby J. Jones (1-2).
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he felt he had his best fastball and best slider that
he's had this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Against Martinez, I left a fastball over the plate,'' he said.
''The next guy never had a bat in his hands. I tried to make a good
pitch and he hit it. Anyone with a bat in his hands is dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez homered with two outs in the Tampa Bay second after
Jones walked John Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   Yan (3-3), batting because there's no DH in interleague games at
NL parks, hit the next pitch into the left-field bullpen for a 3-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets came back in their half of the second when Mike Piazza
walked and scored on Jay Payton's fourth home run. New York tied it
in the third when Kurt Abbott was hit by a pitch and scored on
Piazza's double off the glove of left fielder Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Joe McEwing opened the Mets fifth with a triple and scored on
Piazza's sacrifice fly for a 4-3 lead, but the Devil Rays came
right back, batting around and scoring five runs in the sixth on
just three hits and three walks.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' two-run double capped the big inning as the Devil Rays
rallied for the victory. Vaughn opened with an infield single,
McGriff walked and Flaherty hit an RBI single that tied it at 4.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Cairo walked, loading the bases and then reliever Pat
Mahomes walked Martinez, forcing in the go-ahead run. Pinch-hitter
Jose Guillen bounced out, scoring Flaherty, and Williams doubled
for two more runs.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Williams delivered a sacrifice fly and Russ
Johnson had an RBI single before Trammell's homer as Tampa added
five more runs against reliever Rich Rodriguez following an error
by Abbott at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The scoreboard identified Tampa Bay rookie Steve Cox as the
active leader in grand slams with 14. That distinction belongs to
Robin Ventura of the Mets. The oversight was corrected in Ventura's
first at-bat. ... The Mets have at least one home run in 25 of the
last 31 games and 14 homers in the last eight games. ... McGriff
hit his 400th career home run Friday night at Shea Stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
