<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheers, boos and a handshake as candidates do Israel parade  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton shook hands with her past
and present opponents in the Senate race at the Salute to Israel
parade on Sunday, but she was dogged by hecklers throughout the
22-block march along Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of Clinton campaign volunteers turned out to cheer her,
but they were largely drowned out by cries of ''Go home, Hillary!''
</P>
<P>
   ''The first lady should be marching in the parade for Yasser
Arafat,'' said Ron Torossian, an Israeli immigrant who lives in the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Torossian and other critics remain angry at Clinton because she
sat silently last year while Arafat's wife, Soha, accused the
Israelis of using ''poison gas'' against the Palestinians. Clinton
and Mrs. Arafat embraced at the conclusion of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary Kisses Terrorists,'' said one sign. ''Hillary loves
Soha,'' read another.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, cheers abounded for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and his
successor as the GOP Senate candidate, Rep. Rick Lazio of Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rudy! Rudy! Rudy!'' shouted Dan Lindenfeld of Woodmere as
Clinton strolled by. Reminded that the mayor is no longer running,
he said, ''What's his name? La-zi-o!''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton shook hands with the mayor and Lazio at the parade
reviewing stand. It was the first time Clinton and Lazio had met
since he entered the race two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked him how he was doing, asked him how his daughters were
enjoying the campaign,'' Clinton said. ''We just exchanged some
pleasantries. It was a really nice occasion. We were stressing the
need for bipartisan, non-partisan, above-partisanship support for
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference before the parade with Giuliani, Lazio said
he stood ''four-square behind Israel ... our strongest and only
democratic partner in the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   He endorsed the plan to move the U.S. Embassy in Israel, which
is now in Tel Aviv, to ''the undivided capital of the state of
Israel, Jerusalem.'' Clinton holds the same position.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of a Palestinian state, Lazio said: ''I have
some serious questions about whether or not a Palestinian state is
sustainable, considering the security concerns of the state of
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Before running for the Senate, Clinton said a Palestinian state
was ''important,'' but more recently she has said it should be
decided in negotiations with the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   But she did take a swipe at Lazio's courting the endorsement of
the Independence Party, which is the state arm of the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see how anybody who would wish to represent all of New
York could be on a ticket with Pat Buchanan,'' she said. ''I
roundly reject his anti-Semitism and his prejudicial comments.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also shrugged off the boos she got from parade-goers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are people who support you and people who don't,'' she
said. ''That's part of America. One of the great experiences of
anybody running for office in our country is you know you've got to
go out and earn every vote and convince people that you're right on
the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Two couples from Brooklyn watched the candidates pass by with
mixed feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Kaplan said she was undecided about Lazio but would never
support Clinton. ''What do I think of Hillary? You don't want to
know,'' she said. ''I don't think she belongs here. What does she
know about New York?''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Stanley, said he supported Clinton's support for
the Mideast peace process -- including her earlier support for a
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's right in line with my view of the world,'' said Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   Their friends, Norman and Phyllis Weiss, are backing Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't support Hillary because she has a lot to prove, that
she's not just a carpetbagger,'' Norman Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   Later Sunday, Giuliani, Clinton and Lazio attended the
Philippines Independence Day parade. Lazio worked the crowd dressed
in a traditional embroidered white shirt called a barong, while
Clinton was greeted by a group of scantily clad tribal drummers.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady began Sunday at the annual breakfast for the
Metropolitan Council on Jewish Poverty, a non-partisan organization
that has worked in the past with Lazio on housing issues.
</P>
<P>
   The group traditionally bars anyone but elected officials from
speaking at the breakfast, but Met Council director William
Rapfogel said he was informed by the first lady's office that her
position is equivalent to that of an elected official. The group's
board of directors then agreed that she could speak.
</P>
<P>
   Before Giuliani was elected mayor, he was denied permission to
speak at the breakfast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-04-00 1746 </TRAILER>
