<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine and Florio exchange barbs on final weekend  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Trading recriminations to the end,
Democrats Jon Corzine and Jim Florio marked the final weekend of
their Senate primary battle by sparring over Corzine's spending and
a brochure produced by Florio backers.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, during a public schedule spanning 13 hours on Sunday,
accused Corzine of trying to use his personal wealth to buy a seat
in the U.S. Senate. Corzine, on pace to spend a record-breaking $33
million on the Senate primary, said people are concerned with money
from special interests, not from a candidate's own pocket.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest dustup, Corzine complained about a four-page
brochure distributed by the Camden County Democratic organization,
which supports Florio. The brochure alleges a link between Corzine
and slavery because Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. financed an oil venture in
Sudan during Corzine's tenure at the Wall Street investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tell Jon Corzine not to profit from slavery in Africa!'' reads
its cover.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine called the mailing untrue, divisive and an indication
the Florio camp believes ''you need to be negative'' in order to
win African-American voters.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said he had nothing to do with preparation of the
brochure but defended its tone and substance.
</P>
<P>
   ''The linkage between his efforts and these activities that are
reprehensible is fairly clear,'' Florio said.
</P>
<P>
   Appealing for support in Tuesday's primary, Florio courted
minority, senior and labor votes during morning stops in Burlington
County.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Boyea of Roebling, who heard Florio address the Burlington
County AFL-CIO Central Labor Council meeting, said he supports
Florio's government record and opposes Corzine's campaign strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are tired of big money and big business. Corzine has
just about admitted he's buying this thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to fuel a voter backlash, Florio prepared his supporters
for an unprecedented get-out-the-vote drive by Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's going to spend in one day, to try to buy voters, what I
have spent in my entire campaign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Florio said, ''we have people who are in a crusade,
who say public office should not be bought. I think crusaders
always beat mercenaries.''
</P>
<P>
   At an afternoon rally in Hoboken, Florio was greeted by the
theme song from ''Rocky.'' He told 75 supporters, ''What we're
doing is going up and down the length and breadth of New Jersey
giving a message: New Jersey is not for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine spent the day campaigning alongside the man he hopes to
succeed, Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J. Lautenberg, who chose not to
seek a fourth term in the Senate, has urged voters to elect Corzine
as his replacement.
</P>
<P>
   At a festival in the ethnically diverse neighborhoods of
Harrison, Corzine heard himself addressed as ''senator'' in half a
dozen different accents.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Mayor Ray McDonough escorted Corzine through the city's
streets, introducing him to residents, police officers and priests.
The only sour note: three times Corzine shot a basketball, and
three times he missed.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Licata, taking a break from selling sweet and hot peppers,
said Corzine's wealth is a plus, not a negative.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I like about him is, he came from nothing,'' Licata said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, using strong language to condemn Corzine's campaign
for employing private investigators, Florio declined to say whether
he would support Corzine in November if he is the party nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said Sunday he trusts that ''cooler heads'' will prevail
once the primary is over.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all want Democrats in these important offices,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-04-00 1752 </TRAILER>
