<HEADLINE> Corzine and Franks collect additional endorsements  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Democrats Jon Corzine and Jim Florio and
Republican Bob Franks won additional endorsements from New Jersey
newspapers on Sunday, while Republican Murray Sabrin picked up his
first.
</P>
<P>
   With little enthusiasm, The Trentonian of Trenton endorsed
Corzine over former Gov. Jim Florio but called both men
''bedraggled candidates covered from head to toe with mud.''
</P>
<P>
   In its editorial, the newspaper said Corzine brings to the race
''the potentially useful perspective of a political outsider and a
successful businessman.'' But it added, ''We share the general
revulsion over the incredible sums of money Corzine has spent, even
though it is his own dough.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has also been endorsed by The Times of Trenton and New
York's Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   The Courier-Post of Camden endorsed Florio, saying Democrats on
Tuesday will ''decide if there's a price tag attached to their
party.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio previously received the backing of The Star-Ledger of
Newark, The Philadelphia Inquirer, The New York Times, the Daily
Record of Parsippany, The Jersey Journal of Jersey City and the
Record of Hackensack.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, The Trentonian and the Record of
Hackensack threw their support to Franks, R-Berkeley Heights.
</P>
<P>
   The Record cited Franks' experience, including seven years in
Congress and, before that, 13 years in the state Assembly. The
newspaper said Franks ''showed a troubling reactionary bent early
in his Washington career'' but has since moderated his positions.
</P>
<P>
   The Trentonian called Franks ''a moderate, sensible guy who
knows how to run a disciplined, focused campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks previously received the endorsement of The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   The Courier-Post, giving Sabrin his first endorsement, called
him ''an unapologetic defender of personal liberties and an
advocate for less government interference in people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican, state Sen. William Gormley, has been backed
by The Star-Ledger of Newark, The Times of Trenton and The
Philadelphia Inquirer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
