<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Unveils Sex Slave Numbers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Hundreds of women, mainly from the former
Yugoslavia and neighboring countries, are being forced to work in
Britain as prostitutes after being kidnapped or answering phony job
ads, a government report said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, the first attempt by Britain's Home Office to assess
the extent of the sex slave trade, said a survey of police forces
found that 71 women were known to have been smuggled into the
country to work as prostitutes in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But a conservative estimate of the true number in 1998 alone was
at least 142, and the figure could be as high as 1,420, the report,
titled Stopping Traffic, said.
</P>
<P>
   The women are kidnapped or answer advertisements in their home
countries for jobs as au pairs, secretaries or waitresses, the
report said. They were often brought to Britain on false passports
and accompanied by minders posing as a husband or boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   On arrival, traffickers took the women to brothels and seized
the forged documents. They were then made to repay transport costs
-- sometimes put at more than $20,000 -- by working as prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the women working in apartments, massage
parlors and saunas in central London's Soho district, notorious as
a red light area, were foreigners, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Police investigators identified an organized trade in
prostitutes 10 years ago after raiding several brothels run by a
Hong Kong-based crime syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommended creating a new crime of ''sexual
exploitation'' and increasing penalties for forced prostitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 1827 </TRAILER>
