<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BEA 2000: A 'dot' in every sentence  </HEADLINE>
By HILLEL ITALIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- When bookstore owner Michael Powell arrived at
BookExpo America his schedule included leading a seminar on
electronic publishing. He soon discovered he was the one who needed
leading.
</P>
<P>
   ''I figured I knew as much as anybody about it,'' Powell said.
''On Wednesday we had the seminar. By Friday, I realized everything
I said was wrong. Fortunately, everything everybody else said was
wrong, too.''
</P>
<P>
   If you listened carefully the past few days at McCormick Place
you could hear the sound of heads being scratched, eyes opening and
minds processing it all. BookExpo America, which ended Sunday, both
confirmed and continued the rise of digital media in the publishing
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Lectures and panel discussions on e-books, electronic rights and
related issues attracted standing-room-only crowds. The most talked
about speaker wasn't a writer but the founder and CEO of
Amazon.com, Jeff Bezos. Companies either ignored or nonexistent two
years ago found themselves with all the attention they could
handle.
</P>
<P>
   ''There seems to be a 'dot' in every sentence now,'' said
Stephen Corrick, a literary agent based in Chicago. ''It's been
around the fringes, but this is the first time it's gotten to the
middle of the discussion. It's a period of great excitement and
confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   After a year marked by Stephen King's electronic novella
''Riding the Bullet'' and multimillion dollar investments by
everyone from Microsoft to Random House, few were doubting that
online bookselling and print on-demand would catch on. The question
was when. Some said in a decade, or three years, or six months.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think people will see this as one of the most significant
moments in publishing history,'' Powell said. ''It's coming down
the road at lightning speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistics released over the weekend confirmed how quickly the
market is changing. A study reported that books sold online tripled
their market share between 1998 and 1999, from 1.9 percent to 5.4
percent. More than 50 million titles were purchased by adults and
no one doubts that number will increase significantly next year.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is nothing we can imagine slowing down that trend,''
said Barrie Rappaport of NPD Group Inc., whose firm did the study.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the ones most in danger of being damaged by Internet
sales appear to be independent stores, which already have been hurt
badly by superstore chains. Their market share dropped from 16.6
percent to 15.2 percent in 1999, less than half of what they
controlled 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The CEO of the American Booksellers Association, which
represents thousands of independent sellers, predicted the Internet
would also benefit his group's members. Avin Mark Domnitz said that
BookSense.com, a home page providing links to independent stores,
should be ready by the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're going to see real changes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the industry also talked books, the paper kind. Many
a bookseller (and journalist) visited the booth of Scholastic,
Inc., seeking in vain an early copy of the next Harry Potter story.
The fourth in author J.K. Rowling's series, title and content both
still a mystery, is due July 8.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipated titles for the fall include Margaret Atwood's novel
''The Blind Assassin''; ''The Island of Lost Maps,'' a nonfiction
work by Miles Harvey about cartographic crime, and new books from
Jane Hamilton, Caleb Carr and David Baldacci.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know which medium will be carrying the message, but I
still think paper will be carrying the vast bulk for a long time,''
said Wendy J. Strothman, an executive vice president at Houghton
Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Internet is very exciting, but you miss that opportunity
for customers to browse, that serendipity of finding a book on the
front table of an independent bookstore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-04-00 1836 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000604.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Griffey's Bat Hurts Red Owner's Kin  </HEADLINE>
By JOE KAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Ken Griffey Jr. felt bad when the bat flew
from his hands and conked a 10-year-old girl on the head.
</P>
<P>
   Later on, he got more bad news. It wasn't just any young fan who
wound up with a gash on her forehead in the fourth inning Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was Lindner's granddaughter, right?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's bat hit the granddaughter of Cincinnati Reds owner
Carl Lindner on the left side of the head, forcing the family to
leave the game for a trip to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-year-old Christine Lindner was reportedly doing fine after
getting a few stitches for the cut. That was a relief for Griffey,
who's had two tough months with his hometown team.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm gone,'' Griffey joked. ''You hit .200 and the owner's
granddaughter?
</P>
<P>
   Griffey singled and struck out three times Sunday during a 3-2
victory over Minnesota in 10 innings, leaving his batting average
at .210. He has six hits in his last 50 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The bat accident happened on Ken Griffey Jr. Growth Chart Day, a
promotion that drew 40,169 paying customers. Some fans unrolled
their life-size charts to use as banners.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey took a big swing at a pitch from Mark Redman in the
fourth. The black bat flew from his hands and went twirling towards
the Reds dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Lindner and Reds chief operating officer John Allen were seated
in the row directly behind the 10-year-old girl. Allen leaned
forward to shield her, but couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was trying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Allen moved down a row to help the girl. A trainer in the dugout
tossed Allen a towel to soak up the blood coming from her forehead.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey stood outside the batter's box watching. The game was
held up for a couple of minutes, until it became apparent that the
girl was not seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Lindner and others in his group walked up the aisle behind the
girl as she was taken for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''You just feel bad,'' Griffey said. ''You don't want to hurt
anybody, but those things just happen.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wouldn't mind as much if it was an adult but when it's a
kid, that's the kind of thing that ruins an at-bat or your whole
day. You just don't want to see things like that happen unless it's
some loudmouth who's been on you the whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey struck out swinging to finish the at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Lindner approved the nine-year, $116.5 million contract that
brought Griffey home as part of a trade with Seattle last February.
Lindner sent his private jet to fly Griffey to Cincinnati from
Florida when the deal was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Lindner bought the team last September from Marge Schott, who
often sat in a front-row seat next to the dugout. She was hit in
the left shoulder by a foul ball from Atlanta's Ozzie Virgil on May
8, 1986, but wasn't seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Schott went to a first-aid room for an exam after getting hit,
but later returned to her seat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 1838 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000604.0059 </DOCNO>
