<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reds' Fernandez Injures Elbow  </HEADLINE>
By JOE KAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Cincinnati Reds starter Osvaldo Fernandez left
at the start of the fourth inning Sunday after hurting his elbow on
a swing in the previous half-inning.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, trying to come back from two major elbow operations,
hit a soft liner to second for the second out in the third inning
against Minnesota's Mark Redman.
</P>
<P>
   As he warmed up to start the fourth, pitching coach Don Gullett
went to home plate umpire Tony Randazzo before heading out to the
mound to check on Fernandez's condition.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Benito Santiago and shortstop Barry Larkin joined
Gullett to translate because Fernandez speaks little English. The
pitcher said a few words, pointed at his elbow and left the mound
with his head down.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays found no fracture and the injury was diagnosed as a
jammed elbow. It was too early to tell whether Fernandez will have
to miss a start.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hurt it swinging the bat when I lofted the ball to the
second baseman,'' Fernandez said, with Santiago acting as
translator. ''It's nothing serious. We'll just ice it for a couple
of days and I should make my next start.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted he was scared when it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ''It hurt, then it started getting better and that was a good
sign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Timothy Kremchek said the injury didn't appear to be
serious.
</P>
<P>
   ''He may or may not miss his next start,'' Kremchek said. ''We
took him out for precautionary reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds wound up beating Minnesota 3-2 in 10 innings. They've
won all five of the games that Fernandez has started.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, 31, missed most of the last two years because of
elbow problems. He had the elbow cleaned out in 1997 and had
reconstructive surgery on May 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He failed to win a spot on the Reds' roster in spring training,
but was called up after Pete Harnisch went on the disabled list
with a weak shoulder on May 13.
</P>
<P>
   He went 2-0 in his first four starts for the Reds and was coming
off one of the finest performances of his career. Fernandez allowed
only two hits in seven innings and retired the last 19 batters he
faced in a 2-0 victory over Montreal last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After that game, Fernandez said he was pitching better than
before the operations.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, a mainstay on Cuba's gold medal Olympic team in
Barcelona in 1992, defected in 1995 and was signed by San
Francisco. He went 10-17 with a 4.70 in 41 games for the Giants
from 1996-98.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 1839 </TRAILER>
