<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rioting at Drug Treatment Center  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Police were searching Sunday for about 400
prisoners who fled a drug treatment center for convicted criminals
following a riot that left at least 19 people injured.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners escaped after violence broke out between
Vietnamese and Hong Kong inmates at the Hei Ling Chau center on an
outlying island, the Correctional Services Department said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The sparely populated island is located far from Hong Kong's
urban areas so there was little likelihood that the prisoners could
remain at large for long.
</P>
<P>
   The Hei Ling Chau center was built in 1975 to treat male drug
addicts convicted of crimes. It is run by the Correctional Services
Department and has slightly more than 400 inmates.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear what triggered the argument between the inmates,
who fought each other with iron pipes and homemade weapons.
</P>
<P>
   S.Y. Pang, Deputy Commissioner of the Correctional Services,
said the prisoners set fire to some offices in the center and at
one stage threatened to ignite a liquefied petroleum gas cylinder.
</P>
<P>
   Four injured Correctional Services officers were flown out of
the island by a helicopter for treatment at a hospital on the main
Hong Kong island, he said. Eight police officers and seven inmates
also were injured and treated.
</P>
<P>
   Marine police boats surrounded the island after receiving a call
for assistance from the drug center. Prison officers regained
control of the situation after four hours, Pang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
