<DOCNO> APW20000604.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devils on Road to Stanley Cup  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN ROBINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- The road to the Stanley Cup is proving to be
exactly that for the New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks after needing an exceptional comeback just
to stay alive in the playoffs, the Devils now need only avoid a big
comedown to win their second Stanley Cup championship since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, underdogs to the defending champion Dallas Stars
when the series began, take a 2-1 lead into Game 4 Monday night
following their 2-1 victory Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know what this game means now,'' Devils defenseman Scott
Stevens said Sunday. ''It means being tied 2-2 or ahead 3-1. It's a
big game.''
</P>
<P>
   Or even bigger than Saturday's game, one that could have swung
the series New Jersey's way. Eighteen of the last 21 teams to win
Game 3 in a previously tied series won the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're doing to us what we'd like to be doing to them,''
Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils are doing it with a top line that is paid a combined
salary less than 60 NHL players make by themselves, with a road
show that plays well no matter how hostile the venue. They are 8-2
on the road, with three consecutive victories -- a near carbon copy
of the formula they used to win the Stanley Cup in 1995, when they
were 10-1 away from home.
</P>
<P>
   ''But this has been much harder than 1995,'' goaltender Martin
Brodeur said. ''The only time we were down in any series that year
was 1-0 to Pittsburgh.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Devils won twice each in Florida and Toronto,
then won three times in Philadelphia while rallying from a 3-1
deficit in the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, we're really confident and staying patient and
staying with it until we win the Stanley Cup,'' forward Patrik
Elias said.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Devils coach Larry Robinson, asked before Game 3 if
the goal was to gain a split in Dallas, said, ''We're coming here
to win both games.''
</P>
<P>
   Both?
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know how to explain it,'' said Robinson, an assistant
last season when the Devils set a NHL regular-season record for
road victories. ''Maybe it's the fact our team tries to keep the
game a little more simple. Maybe we feed off the other team's
crowd. I really don't have an answer for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock didn't, either, when asked about his stars' inability
to get going in two of the three games. The Stars were blown out
7-3 in Game 1, needed two goals from Brett Hull to sneak away with
a 2-1 decision in Game 2, then were shut down again Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Devils' top line of Elias, Jason Arnott and Petr
Sykora dominated Dallas' No. 1 line, with Arnott and Sykora each
scoring their third goal of the series. Combined, they have 14
points in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's nice playing with two guys who care about the game as
much as you do and want to win as badly as you do,'' said Arnott, a
Canadian who is flanked on his line by two players from the Czech
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' top line of Hull, Mike Modano and Jere Lehtinen, by
contrast, went scoreless in Game 3, even though Modano
double-shifted much of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a second line that has badly missed the injured Jamie
Langenbrunner (knee) didn't contribute any offense. Joe Nieuwendyk,
last year's playoffs MVP, is scoreless in the series, and no doubt
will welcome Langenbrunner's expected return Monday. Hitchcock
anticipates him to play.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it doesn't seem to add up. Arnott makes $1.8 million and
Elias and Sykora made $625,000 each; a combined salary of $3.05
million. That's half the $6 million that Modano makes. Hull makes
$5.5 million and Lehtinen is paid $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm, that's $3.05 million for 14 New Jersey points and $13
million for four Stars points.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all the offense the Devils' line is producing,
Hitchcock is more concerned about the Stars' inability to solve New
Jersey's neutral zone trap defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Jersey makes you pay a healthy price to get in those areas
to score,'' Hitchcock said. ''At the end of the day, you are going
to have to decide whether the Cup and the accolades that go with it
are worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the possibility of falling behind 3-1 in the Stanley Cup
finals will create that sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, we're disappointed we lost, disappointed to be down
in the series,'' said defenseman Derian Hatcher, who was on the ice
for both New Jersey goals in Game 3. ''But we talked about it and
we'll bounce back for Game 4. We have a choice. It's fight on or
quit.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Stars win Monday, they will be 2-2, just as they were in
last year's finals against Buffalo. The difference is they must
play Game 5 and, if necessary, Game 7 on the road. Even if they win
Game 4, they will have only one more game in Reunion Arena, where
they had won 11 of their last 12 playoff games before Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hey, we're in the Stanley Cup finals,'' Kirk Muller of the
Stars said. ''Nobody said it would be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   One statistic in their favor: the Stars have won their last nine
playoff games following a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Jersey is a team with a very steely exterior and
interior,'' Hitchcock said. ''They are as determined as we are. If
we're waiting to put it into gear, it's not going to work. We've
got to go now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 1851 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000604.0063 </DOCNO>
