<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Free Press in Russia  </HEADLINE>
By WALTER R. MEARS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- President Clinton recommended a free and open
press as ''an instrument of stability'' in a democratic Russia --
even if what is printed hurts. He said he ought to know because no
modern American official has faced more negative or painful
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gave his lecture on freedom of the press Sunday night on
a Moscow radio talk show after the host suggested that any
president would at times have a desire to squash the press for
hounding him and looking for dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ''Have you ever had a desire to shake a journalist real
strong?'' asked Aleksey Venediktov.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't really answer that one.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said it is inevitable that any political leader will
see things he believes to be untrue or unfair, ''and you can get
angry.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said ''we think that democracy is more stable and people
are more free when the press is free. And we trust the people to
understand if the press is either false or unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said ''when someone says something about me that's not
true, I can go on a program like this, and I can say here's what
they say, here's the truth. I can go on television. I can give a
speech.''
</P>
<P>
   He has done all the above during his travails over Whitewater,
the long investigation that eventually led to the Monica Lewinsky
scandal and to his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't mention any of that. He was in instructional
mode.
</P>
<P>
   He said that even when a free press acts irresponsibly, ''you
still have more stability in society by letting people be free, by
letting the debates unfold, and by trusting that the citizens, the
voters, in the end will get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he and Russian President Vladimir Putin had discussed
press freedom in their summit talks. ''I quoted his statement,
President Putin said that without civil society and a free press,
the Russian democracy couldn't go on,'' he said. ''And I think
that's a wise statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said that ''this is something that has to be
debated and fought for and struggled for,'' something that has
taken the United States two centuries, while Russia has just begun.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been working on this a long time,'' Clinton said. ''But
the trend has always been for more freedom of the press,
particularly where public issues and public officials are
concerned,'' he said. ''It's served us well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
