<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Golfers Get Tips from Tiger  </HEADLINE>
By AARON J. LOPEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- The fluid swing and made-for-TV pose after the
ball takes flight quickly attracts a group of curious spectators,
reporters and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Some shots flying off the battered, kid-sized driver go slightly
right or left but most are down the middle, prompting one observer
to speculate on the young boy's future as golf's next phenom.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's get him through kindergarten first,'' says Edna Herring,
who's 5-year-old grandson, R.J. Young, was among about 125 children
invited Sunday to a junior golf clinic sponsored by the Tiger Woods
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a Titleist visor and Nike clothing favored by his idol,
R.J. received tips from Denver-area pros while the 24-year-old
Woods gave personal instruction to 25 hand-selected players ranging
in age from 10 to 18.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I probably have more credibility with these kids just
because I am close to their age,'' Woods said. ''For example, I
don't really understand what Elgin Baylor, Jerry West, Wilt
Chamberlain and Bill Russell did for the game of basketball. I
wasn't around. But I know what M.J. (Michael Jordan) did. That
lends more credibility if these kids have grown up watching me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicki Birdsong, the Class 5A state champion, is just six years
younger than Woods and showed no sign of being star struck as she
popped shot after shot high into the air with the world's
top-ranked golfer offering bits of advice from a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ''You just have to breathe deep and hope you don't miss the
ball,'' said Birdsong, who will play for the University of Denver
next year. ''I've met other pro players before, but this was such a
thrill because he's so much closer to my age.''
</P>
<P>
   The admiration is mutual. Woods said he is amazed at the talent
level of young golfers across the country. With two more of his
junior golf clinics scheduled this summer in New Orleans and
Norfolk, Va., Woods may be providing the building blocks for future
rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was growing up and playing junior golf, there were only
a handful of us that were any good,'' he said, ''but now there are
kids all around the country who hit the ball further than I did,
straighter than I did. They're getting bigger and stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen-year-old Justin Tafoya is among the new breed of young
golfers. He started swinging a club when he was about 3 and likely
will play varsity golf as a freshman next fall at Denver East High
School.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to receiving personal attention from Woods, Tafoya
also came away with a better impression of the influential
millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was completely the opposite of what I thought,'' Tafoya
said. ''I thought he would be a stuck-up kind of guy, but he's
nice. It's incredible. He's that guy on TV that you'll never meet.
It's just amazing to finally meet him.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, whose popularity rivals Jordan, said he is humbled by
children who consider him a role model, and his sincerity is
confirmed as he patiently works with young students on everything
from their grip and stance to their posture and head position.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is something I believe in,'' Woods said. ''I think that's
what comes across and I think that's why the kids really respond.
If you put an athlete or any person into a position where they
don't really believe in it, then obviously it's not going to come
across.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 1906 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000604.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warrick Agrees to Bengals Contract  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- First-round draft pick Peter Warrick has
agreed to a seven-year contract worth $42 million with the
Cincinnati Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals' Web site reported that Warrick was expected to sign
the contract Sunday night at the home of team executive vice
president Katie Blackburn. The team was to formally announce the
deal at a Monday morning news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, a wide receiver from Florida State, was the fourth
overall pick in the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   He will get more than $10 million in signing and reporting
bonuses this year, said his agent, Jim Gould.
</P>
<P>
   The contract contains a seventh voidable year, meaning the deal
could be shortened to six years if Warrick plays 45 percent of the
downs in any season.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day contract negotiations ended at noon Sunday when
Blackburn met Gould at her home in the Cincinnati suburb of Indian
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone in the room is counting on him making the full $42
million,'' Gould said. ''It's very doable.''
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations were the Bengals' shortest with a first-round
pick since Ohio State's Dan Wilkinson signed his seven-year, $14.4
million contract in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick is the third first-round pick to agree to a contract
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Browns defensive end Courtney Brown and New York Jets
tight end Anthony Becht also have come to terms.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick won't work out with the Bengals until he completes more
of the community service sentence he received in Florida after
pleading guilty to a petty theft charge.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, a former Florida State teammate and a store clerk were
charged after the two players paid $21.40 for more than $400 worth
of clothes last Sept. 29 at a Dillard's department store in
Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   He will remain in Florida cleaning up trash along highways as
part of his 30-day sentence. His agents expect him to complete the
sentence before training camp starts July 21, the Bengals' Web site
reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 1907 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000604.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Senate candidates court the faithful, seeking plurality  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The four Republican candidates for New
Jersey's U.S. Senate seat courted core supporters Sunday, each
hoping to produce enough votes to assemble a plurality on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. William Gormley, R-Atlantic, spent the day in Ocean
and Atlantic counties, tending to his base in southern New Jersey.
Rep. Bob Franks, R-Berkeley Heights, toured areas of the state
where his past service as state party chairman has helped him earn
organization support.
</P>
<P>
   Ramapo College economics professor Murray Sabrin, the most
socially conservative candidate, said he was cheered by gun owners
he met in northwestern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   And Essex County Executive Jim Treffinger, eschewing public
events, visited key county supporters around the state to plan how
to get out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on core supporters reflected the political reality
of a four-candidate primary field. As Sabrin said, ''You don't need
51 percent to win. You just need, theoretically, 26 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   In Absecon, where beer flowed by the keg and pizza disappeared
by the tray, Gormley's smile and vigorous handshake highlighted
that he felt comfortably at home.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley met with some 80 of his party's faithful in a grove
outside an American Legion hall. Though he spent Saturday in
northern New Jersey, Gormley made clear that he is counting on the
southern part of the state on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody is saying, especially in North Jersey, that (the
race) is undecided,'' Gormley said. ''Well, I will tell you this.
It is decided in South Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks disagrees. His ''Franks on a Roll'' bus tour stopped
Sunday in such southern locales as Burlington and Gloucester
counties.
</P>
<P>
   ''When (Gormley) says he's South Jersey's candidate, he's only
partly right,'' Glenn Paulsen, the Burlington County GOP chairman,
told 50 Franks supporters outside party headquarters in Mount
Holly. ''He's a South Jersey guy, but he's not South Jersey's
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks won the endorsement of the Burlington GOP, giving him a
favored position on the primary ballot.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to the crowd, Franks took aim at the two Democratic
candidates for Senate, Jon Corzine and Jim Florio. Asked later why
he seemed to be looking past Tuesday's primary, Franks replied,
''We are going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Treffinger spent most of the weekend meeting privately with each
of his county coordinators throughout the state, planning a phone
bank operation to get supporters to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've decided to purposely forgo the usual photo-op stuff and
just take care of business,'' Treffinger said. ''I'm going to meet
with all my coordinators and make sure all my phone lists are done.
The whole object now is identify the vote as scientifically as we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabrin was preparing to wrap up his campaign with a nonstop,
24-hour tour of New Jersey diners in all 21 counties beginning at 7
a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   His stops Sunday included a crawfish festival in Stanhope, where
long lines prevented him from tasting the catch of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, his campaign aggressively disputed charges
that Sabrin, who ran for governor as a Libertarian in 1997, shares
that party's support for decriminalizing drug use and prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter last week to supporters, Sabrin wrote, ''I have
never advocated the legalization of drugs, prostitution or gay
marriages.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as they battle for a victory on Tuesday, the Republican
candidates cannot help but look across the party divide at what the
victor may face in the fall: Corzine, and his proven willingness to
spend tens of millions of his own dollars to win.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have thought about that,'' Treffinger said. ''I imagine
everybody has.''
</P>
<P>
   Gormley, joking about Corzine's estimated $400 million in
personal wealth, said Republicans will give him a battle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until now, Corzine has been spending interest from his
wealth,'' Gormley said. ''We are going to make sure he has to spend
some of his principal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
