<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warrick OKs $42M Deal with Bengals  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- First-round draft pick Peter Warrick has
agreed to a seven-year contract worth $42 million with the
Cincinnati Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals' Web site reported that Warrick was expected to sign
the contract Sunday night at the home of team executive vice
president Katie Blackburn. The team was to formally announce the
deal at a Monday morning news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, a wide receiver from Florida State, was the fourth
overall pick in the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   He will get more than $10 million in signing and reporting
bonuses this year, said his agent, Jim Gould.
</P>
<P>
   The contract contains a seventh voidable year, meaning the deal
could be shortened to six years if Warrick plays 45 percent of the
downs in any season.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day contract negotiations ended at noon Sunday when
Blackburn met Gould at her home in the Cincinnati suburb of Indian
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone in the room is counting on him making the full $42
million,'' Gould said. ''It's very doable.''
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations were the Bengals' shortest with a first-round
pick since Ohio State's Dan Wilkinson signed his seven-year, $14.4
million contract in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick is the third first-round pick to agree to a contract
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Browns defensive end Courtney Brown and New York Jets
tight end Anthony Becht also have come to terms.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick won't work out with the Bengals until he completes more
of the community service sentence he received in Florida after
pleading guilty to a petty theft charge.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, a former Florida State teammate and a store clerk were
charged after the two players paid $21.40 for more than $400 worth
of clothes last Sept. 29 at a Dillard's department store in
Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   He will remain in Florida cleaning up trash along highways as
part of his 30-day sentence. His agents expect him to complete the
sentence before training camp starts July 21, the Bengals' Web site
reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
