<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two 1st-Timers in College Series  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Louisiana-Lafayette and San Jose State are going to
the College
World Series for the first time, and Miami won't get the chance to
repeat as national champion.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Louisiana-Lafayette (47-18) beat top-seeded South Carolina
(56-10) 3-2 Sunday in the best-of-three super regionals to advance
to Omaha, Neb., for the first time in 29 seasons as a Division I
program.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you're a small school, no one ever gives you the credit
for doing things,'' said Rick Haydel, whose two-run double gave the
Ragin' Cajuns a 3-2 lead in the seventh inning. ''It feels amazing
to do something no one thought you could.''
</P>
<P>
   San Jose State (41-22), in the NCAA tournament for the first
time since 1971, beat Houston 3-2 Sunday to secure its first
College World Series appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Miami (41-19-1) was bidding to become just the fifth school to
repeat as national champion, but in-state rival Florida State
(51-17) ended those hopes with a 6-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   In the other super regional Sunday, Stanford advanced with 5-3
victory over Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Clemson, Louisiana State, Southern California and
Texas all advanced to the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Louisiana-Lafayette lost two straight to Rice after
winning the first game of the super regional, and used that memory
as motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't want to forget that feeling,'' catcher Danny
Massiatte said. ''We've used it all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Dohmann (12-5), who allowed just four hits in seven
innings, had the box score from the final Rice defeat taped in his
locker. Now, taking that box score down is at the top of his to-do
list. ''That might be the first thing I do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dohmann's only mistake was a seventh-inning, two-run homer to
Tripp Kelly that gave the Gamecocks a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ragin' Cajuns rallied to do what no other team had been
able to do this season -- beat the nation's winningest team twice on
its home field.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought we would advance; we expected to advance,'' said
South Carolina coach Ray Tanner, tears in his eyes, his voice
catching more than once.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just in disbelief,'' Gamecocks shortstop Drew Meyer
said.
San Jose St. 3, Houston 2:
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, Tim Adinolfi and Chris Key combined on a six-hitter
and Rob Douglass and John Fagan each homered for San Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   Adinolfi (8-3) struck out four, walked three and allowed only
four runners to reach second base in eight innings. Key pitched the
ninth for his second save.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan drove an 0-1 fastball from Houston starter Duncan McAdoo
(7-3) over the left-field wall to give the Spartans a 3-1 lead in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been waiting until I could take a team there,'' said
coach Sam Piraro, in his 14th year with the Spartans. ''I didn't
think I would get there.''
Florida St. 6, Miami 1:
</P>
<P>
   In Tallahassee, Florida State freshman Mike Ziegler (9-4) struck
out nine, surrendered nine hits and did not allow a walk in a
complete game to send the Seminoles to their third consecutive
College World Series, and 18th overall.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the most exciting moment of my career -- to watch these
young men celebrate a victory and accomplish a goal,'' Seminoles
coach Mark Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes, who fell one victory shy of a record-tying
seventh consecutive CWS appearance, grounded into three double
plays and never seriously threatened after scoring a run in the
first on Javy Rodriguez's sacrifice fly.
Stanford 5, Nebraska 3:
</P>
<P>
   In Palo Alto, Calif., Brian Sager (6-1) allowed five hits in
seven innings and Edmund Muth homered to lead Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Sager allowed just one earned run while striking out three and
walking four in his longest outing of the season. Jeff Bruksch got
the final six outs for his 12th save.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Bruntlett had four hits as Stanford (47-15) reached the
College World Series for the third time in four years and 12th
overall.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Strong had two hits for Nebraska (51-17), which just
missed reaching its first College World Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
