<HEADLINE> Notes From Sunday's Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressINTERLEAGUE:
Devil Rays-Mets:
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: Fred McGriff reached another milestone, getting his
2,000th career hit. On Friday night, he hit his 400th home run. ...
Bubba Trammell had his third pinch-hit home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Rick Reed threw 50 pitches off the mound to test his
strained left side and reported no pain. He will throw again Monday
before a final decision is made about his projected start Tuesday
against Baltimore. ... Derek Bell, stuck in a 3-for-42 slump,
rested. ''He's mentally drained,'' manager Bobby Valentine said.
... OF Darryl Hamilton, on the DL since April 7 after foot surgery,
said his recovery is going as planned. ''The next couple of weeks
are important,'' he said. ''If things go well we'll make a decision
on when I can come back.''
Yankees-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: The Yankees got by without C Jorge Posada and OF Paul
O'Neill, who both left Saturday's game with minor injuries. Posada
could have played after taking a foul tip off his right knee,
shattering the shin guard, but he already was scheduled to get the
day off. Chris Turner took his place and went 1-for-4. The
left-handed O'Neill, bothered by soreness in his right leg, didn't
play with Braves starting left-hander Terry Mulholland. Shane
Spencer played right field, going 3-for-5 with one RBI and also
making a nice running catch to end the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Pitcher Don Wengert, called up by the Braves on
Thursday when Greg McMichael went on the disabled list, has yet to
make his Atlanta debut. When he does, he will be pitching for his
fifth team, having previous stints with Oakland, San Diego, the
Chicago Cubs and Kansas City since 1995. ... Steve Avery, trying to
come back from shoulder surgery at Class A Myrtle Beach, has
started twice for the Carolina League team. He is 1-1 with a 1.32
ERA but control has been a problem. He has issued 10 walks in 13
2-3 innings.
Twins-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Mark Redman had never fanned more than seven batters
in a game before striking out nine in Sunday's game. ... The Twins
are 2-4 on a nine-game trip that concludes with three in Houston.
... Redman grounded out in the third and struck out with the bases
loaded in the fourth. Twins pitchers were 2-for-6 with a single and
a double in the series.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Cincinnati improved to 26-20 in interleague play.
Minnesota is 24-27. ... Chris Stynes started in left field for the
first time since Sept. 26, 1998. ... Griffey struck out in the
eighth against Eddie Guardado. He's 2-for-18 career against the
left-hander with nine strikeouts. ... Reds starter Osvaldo
Fernandez jammed his pitching elbow while lining out in the third
inning. Fernandez, who missed most of the 1998-99 seasons because
of two major elbow operations, tried to warm up for the fourth but
had to leave the game. ... The game was held up for a couple of
minutes in the fourth inning, when Ken Griffey's bat slipped from
his hands on a swing and hit a granddaughter of team owner Carl
Lindner. Christine Lindner, 10, was sitting in the first row behind
the Reds dugout when she was hit. She was taken to a hospital for a
few stitches to close a cut on the left side of her forehead. ''You
just feel bad,'' Griffey said. ''You don't want to hurt anybody,
but those things just happen. ... The accident happened on Ken
Griffey Jr. Growth Chart Day, a promotion that drew 40,169 paying
fans.
Orioles-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: Manager Mike Hargrove missed his second straight game
in order to attend son Andy's high school graduation in Cleveland.
Bench coach Jeff Newman filled in. ... The Orioles are 12-26 since
April 22 when they were a season-high six games over .500. ...
Albert Belle went 1-for-4 Sunday and has hit safely in 28 of his
last 31 games, going 39-for-119 (.328) over that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: The Expos raised their interleague record to 29-23,
including a 19-7 mark at home against AL opponents. Montreal, which
also swept a three-game set from Baltimore at Olympic Stadium June
26-28, 1998, is 6-0 at home against the Orioles. ... Geoff Blum
made his second straight start at second base for the injured Jose
Vidro and made two fine plays in the ninth, including sliding to
his left to field B.J. Surhoff's grounder and throwing to first for
the game's final out. ... Vidro, who was given a cortisone shot
Saturday for a sprained ligament in the middle finger of his right
hand, is expected to return to the lineup Tuesday against the
Yankees.
Red Sox-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: SS Nomar Garciaparra did not start Sunday's game, but
hit a pinch-hit infield single in the 10th inning. Garciaparra is
13-for-21 (.619) in his last six games, including two home runs and
two doubles. ... Mike Stanley is in 13-for-74 (.176) slump. Five of
the hits were home runs.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Curt Schilling began his professional career with
the Red Sox. He was the second round selection in the 1986 draft.
... The Phillies will honor their 1980 World Series champions on
June 17. ... P Cliff Politte, who was recalled from Triple-A
Scranton Wilkes-Barre when Paul Byrd was optioned, will make his
first start of the season on Tuesday against Milwaukee.
Royals-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The Royals' hottest hitter was signed to be a
defensive replacement. Kansas City got Dave McCarty with the idea
that he could play the late innings at first base for Mike Sweeney.
Given an opportunity to do more, McCarty has a .354 average and a
12-game hitting streak. There's a lesson in that for all players,
manager Tony Muser believes. ''If you can play a little defense,
you can have more lives,'' he said. ''If all you can do is hit and
you stop hitting, what else can you do? If you can play defense,
you're going to keep getting at bats.'' ... Reliever Jason Rakers
was the winning pitcher Sunday, a big turnaround from Friday's game
that saw him give up five runs in one inning. It was tough for
Rakers because he's from the Pittsburgh suburbs and he had family
and friends in the stands. ''That's more like it,'' he said after
Sunday's win. ... The Royals have won 13 games in their last
at-bat, surpassing last year's total.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Kevin Young, stuck in a 1-for-19 slump that has
lowered his average to .239, heard boos on Sunday. Young was
0-for-6 and left four runners on base. ''I can't let it get to
me,'' he said. ''This isn't like football where you can go out and
take out your frustration and anger on someone else. If anything,
you have to be the exact opposite. You have to stay calm.''
Indians-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Pat Hentgen's interleague start Monday against the
Kansas City Royals is no special occasion. He's 10-6 with a 4.04
career ERA against the Royals from his years in Toronto, including
2-1 last year. ... Jesse Orosco makes his third rehab start Tuesday
for Triple-A Memphis, although it won't last long. Orosco's first
two appearances were also starts and each lasted 12 pitches. He's
expected to be activated in perhaps another week. ... Three
Cardinals farm hands lead their leagues in reliever standings. Gene
Stechschulte has 10 saves for Triple-A Memphis, Corey Avrad has 14
saves for Double-A Arkansas and Jason Marr has 15 saves for Class A
Potomac. ... Ray Lankford sat out Sunday due to a slightly pulled
left hamstring he hurt running the bases on Saturday. ''It will
take a couple of days,'' he said. ''Maybe in another day I can try
to play on it and just don't try to push it too much.''
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: Dave Burba, who starts Monday at Milwaukee, has won
his last four decisions. He hasn't lost since his second start of
the season against the Rangers April 14. ... Eighteen of closer
Steve Karsay's outings have lasted one inning. He has 11 saves in
13 chances. ... Kenny Lofton, who snapped an 0-for-13 slump on
Saturday, had a home run, two singles and a double the last two
games of the series, going 4-for-8. ''I'm trying to do the little
thing and take some good swings at good pitches,'' Lofton said.
Tigers-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: 3B Shane Andrews will undergo back surgery for a
herniated disc and be sidelined a minimum of eight weeks. ...
Pitcher Kerry Wood will get an extra day between starts and go
Saturday against the White Sox. Manager Don Baylor said he will try
to give Wood an extra day whenever possible as the right-hander
continues his comeback from elbow surgery. ... Infielder Augie
Ojeda made his first major league start, starting at shortstop. He
doubled in his third at-bat in the seventh and the crowd chanted
''Augie, Augie.'' The Cubs are thin at shortstop, already losing
Ricky Gutierrez (separated right shoulder) and Jose Nieves
(strained left hamstring). ... Sunday's 12-inning game was the
longest by inning for the Cubs this season.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: RF Juan Gonzalez had to leave Sunday's game after four
innings after fouling a ball off his left foot. Garner said he'll
''wait and see'' whether Gonzalez can play on the artificial turf
in Pittsburgh, starting Monday.
White Sox-Astros:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Frank Thomas, who had started 53 of 54 games and played
in all of them, was given his first full day off this season
Sunday. Thomas was replaced in the lineup by Paul Konerko, who went
3-for-4 with two doubles, a walk and two RBIs. Konerko broke out of
a 1-for-26 slump. ... The White Sox have four pitchers, Kevin
Beirne, Mike Sirotka, Kip Wells and Kelly Wunsch, who are Houston
natives.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Mitch Meluskey is leading all NL rookies in home runs
(seven), RBI (31) and extra base hits (18). His 10 multi-hit games
and 21 walks is also tied for the rookie lead in the majors. ...
Jeff Bagwell, who is 1-for-11 in this homestand, still needs two
RBIs to reach 1,000 for his career.
Giants-Athletics:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: Giants manager Dusty Baker, unhappy with the
team's performance over the last couple days, held a closed-door
meeting with his club before Sunday's interleague series finale at
Oakland. San Francisco lost the first two games at Oakland,
dropping to two games below .500. Baker wouldn't go into specifics
about his decision to call the meeting. ''You just get a feeling,''
Baker said. ''Usually, I talk to guys individually. A couple of
times of year, I feel the need to talk to them as a group. You
don't want to do it too much because it loses impact. The more you
yell at your kids, the less they hear you. I don't expect any
overnight action.'' ... 1B J.T. Snow was back in the lineup Sunday
after missing the previous game because of a bout of food
poisoning. Also available was C Doug Mirabelli, who recovered from
an eye irritation that sidelined him Saturday. ''He can see
today,'' Baker said. ... SS Rich Aurilia, was out of the lineup for
a fourth straight game. He hasn't played since straining his left
hamstring Tuesday. Baker said he was available Sunday in an
emergency. ''We just don't want him to pull it completely and then
be out.''
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: Reliever Mike Magnante is the only Oakland player
remaining on the DL and manager Art Howe said his rehabilitation of
a strained left hamstring is coming along nicely. ''He's improving
every day,'' Howe said of Magnante, who went on the DL May 27. The
A's had some injury problems early in the season but are now close
to full health with Saturday's return of DH John Jaha from a
shoulder strain. 2B Randy Velarde has come back strong after
missing the first 31 games of the season with a knee injury. ''I
hope all these injuries are behind us,'' Howe said.
Dodgers-Angels:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: Reliever Gregg Olson, on the DL with a strained
forearm since April 9, began a rehabilitation stint with Class A
San Bernardino. ... OF Todd Hollandsworth missed today's start
after having come out of Saturday's game with a strained right
hamstring. He is available in an emergency, but manager Davey
Johnson hoped to give him a full day of rest. ... Shawn Gilbert
replaced Hollandsworth in center in his first major league start
since 1998, when he was combined 4-for-27 with the Mets and
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: Jarrod Washburn, removed from his previous start with a
tight shoulder after five hitless innings, entered his start Sunday
with an overall string of seven hitless innings and stretched that
to 7 2-3 before Shawn Green's single. ... For years, the Angels
went through a revolving door of second baseman next to iron man SS
Gary DiSarcina. With rookie Adam Kennedy now established at second,
but DiSarcina out for the season following shoulder surgery, Kevin
Stocker has become the team's sixth different shortstop this
season.
Blue Jays-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: INF Tony Batista missed his fifth straight game with a
strained left rib cage. Before the injury, Batista had played 151
consecutive games. ... Three Blue Jays still haven't taken a day
off this season. CF Jose Cruz Jr., 1B Carlos Delgado and SS Alex
Gonzalez have played all of Toronto's 58 games. Cruz and Delgado
haven't missed a start, either. RF Raul Mondesi has only missed one
game this year.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: The Marlins clubhouse is filling up with fish,
literally. ''Big Mouth Billy Bass,'' a mounted rubber fish that
sings songs like ''The River'' and ''Don't Worry, Be Happy,'' is
now a fixture in four lockers. INF Dave Berg bought the first one
Friday for the slumping Alex Gonzalez, hoping to cheer him up.
After Gonzalez got a pair of hits Friday, several Marlins called it
a good luck charm. Now, RHP Ryan Dempster, 1B Kevin Millar and OF
Brant Brown each have a singing fish in their lockers. ... 2B Luis
Castillo missed Sunday's game with a sore left ankle. ''I don't
think one day is going to help it much, but it can't hurt. It just
hasn't healed yet,'' manager John Boles said.
Padres-Mariners:
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: RHP Donne Wall was placed on the 15-day DL
retroactive to June 1 with shoulder tendinitis and recalled RHP
Brandon Kolb from Triple-A Las Vegas. Kolb was 1-1 with a
league-leading 10 saves and a 1.83 ERA (4 ER, 19.2 IP) in 19 games
with Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: The Mariners pitchers have a 3.29 ERA at home, the
lowest in the American League. ... More than half of the Mariners
current 25-man roster played in the National League during their
careers. ... Although Brian Meadows had never faced the Mariners,
the Seattle batters entered the game with a combined .457 average
(16-for-35) against him.
Diamondbacks-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Entering Sunday night's game against the Rangers, the
Diamondbacks played five straight one-run games on the road. They
lost four of them. ... Arizona's bullpen had allowed only one
earned run over its previous seven innings prior to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: Jason McDonald and Scarborough Green will platoon in
center field this week, then Gabe Kapler will take over the job.
Kapler will play three minor league rehab games this week as he
completes his recovery from a partially torn right quad muscle.
Everyday center fielder Ruben Mateo is out for the season with a
fractured right femur. ... The Rangers will recall RHP Ryan Glynn
from Triple-A Oklahoma for Monday night's start against the
Dodgers. LHP Darren Oliver will skip a start due to a tired arm,
but is expected to be back in the rotation next Sunday. ... Rookie
3B Mike Lamb was scratched from the starting lineup due to a
slightly strained right upper back.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Rockies-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Pedro Astacio has pitched nine innings in each of his
last two starts in Milwaukee, but had no-decisions both times. He
allowed one run on Aug. 10, 1999 and one unearned run Saturday
night. ... The Rockies matched their season low with only three
hits in Saturday's 2-1, 12-inning loss at Milwaukee. ''You've just
got to give credit to their pitchers,'' manager Buddy Bell said,
''and you can't expect to win the game with only one run.'' ... The
Rockies start their interleague schedule Monday at Seattle.
Colorado is 17-23 in their first three years of interleague play.
... The Rockies have three of the first 100 selections in Monday's
draft. The seventh pick in the first round is their highest
selection in team history.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Saturday's 2-1 victory in 12 innings over the Rockies
marked the first time since last Sept. 25, 1999 that the Brewers
won when scoring three runs or less. ... Milwaukee is 4-0 in
extra-inning games at home in 2000. ... Manager Davey Lopes has
faith that three regulars -- Jeromy Burnitz, Marquis Grissom and
Jose Hernandez -- will boost their numbers to match previous
seasons. ''I have to believe that,'' Lopes said. ''I can't give up
on these guys. Usually guys get close to what they've been in the
past, so that's something to look forward to in the last 107
games.''
</P>
