<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giants 18, Athletics 2  </HEADLINE>
By DENNIS GEORGATOS
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Barry Bonds hit his major league-leading
23rd home run and Jeff Kent homered twice and doubled twice to
drive in five runs as the San Francisco Giants avoided a sweep by
routing the Oakland Athletics 18-2 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis Burks and Bill Mueller also homered to back Shawn Estes'
seven-hitter and help the Giants match their biggest scoring burst
of the season. Estes, who fanned eight and walked three in his
eighth career complete game, hit a grand slam and threw a shutout
in San Francisco's 18-0 victory over Montreal on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's second road win in the last 12 tries included
six-, five- and four-run innings and followed a closed-door pregame
meeting called by manager Dusty Baker. He was unhappy the Giants
had fallen two games below .500 after starting the series at
Oakland with back-to-back losses.
</P>
<P>
   ''Usually, I talk to guys individually,'' Baker said after the
meeting. ''A couple of times of year, I feel the need to talk to
them as a group. You don't want to do it too much because it loses
impact. The more you yell at your kids, the less they hear you. I
don't expect any overnight action.''
</P>
<P>
   It was more like same-day action.
</P>
<P>
   Estes (5-2) won for the fifth time in six decisions over his
last seven starts, gave up a solo homer to Sal Fasano in the fifth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants set the tone at the outset against Omar Olivares
(3-7), who lost his fourth straight decision while allowing eight
runs and 10 hits in 4 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Benard and Mueller hit successive singles to start the
game and Bonds drove a 2-1 pitch into the right-field bleachers.
Kent then doubled and eventually scored on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Burks connected for a leadoff homer in the fourth and Bobby
Estalella's RBI single put San Francisco up 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, San Francisco sent 10 batters to the plate and
scored six.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds singled ahead of Kent's homer, which chased Olivares.
Scott Service relieved and the first three batters he faced reached
on an error and two walks before Ramon Martinez's two-run double, a
sacrifice fly by Estalella and a run-scoring double by Benard.
</P>
<P>
   Kent hit his 16th homer of the season off Rich Sauveur, a
three-run shot in San Francisco's five-run seventh and Mueller
connected off Sauveur in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Sunday marked the third straight sellout in the series
between the cross-bay rivals and the three-game attendance of
145,288 was the most ever at the Oakland Coliseum for a three-game
set. It eclipsed the 140,876 who turned out to see the New York
Yankees on May 1-3, 1981. ... Kent's two homers marked the 10th
multihomer game of his career and first since June 16 at Colorado.
... Olivares has allowed seven home runs in his last six starts
after allowing one -- an inside the park homer -- in his first six.
He hasn't won since May 7, a span of five starts. ... The Giants
had 19 hits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 1956 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
