<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, June 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indonesian Earthquake Kills At Least 25
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Seismologists said a powerful earthquake and
several strong aftershocks rocked the island of Sumatra, causing at least 25
deaths and leaving thousands homeless. The Indonesian Meteorological and
Geophysical Service said the quake, measuring 7.3, was centered beneath the
Indian Ocean, about 400 miles northwest of Jakarta. The U.S. Geological Survey
in Golden, Colo., reported the earthquake's strength at 7.9. The quake lasted
several minutes and shook a wide area.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
OAS Assembly Begins Monday
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario (AP) -- As hundreds of anti-free trade protesters chanted
outside, foreign ministers from the Organization of American States launched
their annual assembly today, expecting to focus on Peru's presidential election.
The Windsor protest -- which was mirrored by another across the U.S. river
border in Detroit -- brought the OAS, which also deals with trade issues,
face-to-face with the same movement that obstructed December's World Trade
Organization meeting in Seattle. Suffocating security measures and hundreds of
police in riot gear prevented demonstrators from crossing into a security zone
set up within a 10-foot fence around several blocks in downtown Windsor.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Alleged Terrorist Claims Attacks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A man who said he coordinated most of Iran's terror
operations of the last decade claimed responsibility for two major attacks on
the United States, the destruction of Pan Am Flight 103 and the Khobar Towers
bombing, ''60 Minutes'' reported today. The man, whom the CBS News program
identified as Ahmad Behbanani, told a ''60 Minutes'' journalist that he proposed
the 1988 Pan Am operation, brought on board a radical Palestinian terrorist
living in Syria, then imported and trained Libyan operatives to do the job. The
program said his motive was to avenge a U.S. Navy cruiser's mistaken shooting
down five months earlier of an Iranian passenger plane.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Better Anti-Terrorism Campaign Urged
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Officials should consider designating Greece and Pakistan
as countries ''not cooperating fully'' in the battle against terrorism and
strengthen the category by banning those countries' citizens from traveling here
without visas, a blue-ribbon commission says. Pakistan provides ''safe haven,
transit and moral, political and diplomatic support to several groups engaged in
terrorism'' and Greece -- a NATO ally -- ''has been disturbingly passive in
response to terrorist activities,'' according to the National Commission on
Terrorism, a panel of private experts and former government officials. The
commission is due to report to lawmakers on Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report Cites Japanese As Healthiest
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- The World Health Organization said Sunday that the Japanese
have the best prospects for long and active lives, and can expect 74{ years of
healthy life. A WHO study measured ''disability-adjusted'' life expectancy,
subtracting years according to the prevalence and severity of ailments ranging
from malaria to lung disease. Americans lag behind because of miserable
standards among the U.S. poor -- who fare worse than many Africans. Australia,
at 73.2 years, came second, followed by France, Sweden, Spain and Italy. The
United States rated only 24th, with an expectancy of 70 years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rioting at Hong Kong Drug Center
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Police were searching Sunday for about 400 prisoners who
fled a drug treatment center for convicted criminals following a riot that left
at least 19 people injured. The prisoners escaped after violence broke out
between Vietnamese and Hong Kong inmates at the Hei Ling Chau center on an
outlying island, the Correctional Services Department said in a statement. The
sparely populated island is located far from Hong Kong's urban areas so there
was little likelihood that the prisoners could remain at large for long.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Urges Free Press in Russia
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- President Clinton recommended a free and open press in a
democratic Russia -- even if what is printed hurts. He said he ought to know
because no modern American official has faced more negative or painful
reporting. Clinton gave his lecture on freedom of the press Sunday night on a
Moscow radio talk show after the host suggested that any president would at
times have a desire to squash the press for hounding him and looking for dirt.
Clinton said that even when a free press acts irresponsibly, ''you still have
more stability in society by letting people be free, by letting the debates
unfold, and by trusting that the citizens, the voters, in the end will get it
right.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Giants Rout Athletics 18-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Barry Bonds hit his major league-leading 23rd home
run and Jeff Kent homered twice and doubled twice to drive in five runs as the
San Francisco Giants routed the Oakland Athletics 18-2 today. Ellis Burks and
Bill Mueller also homered to back Shawn Estes' seven-hitter.
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA 
</P>
