<HEADLINE> Ireland 2, Mexico 2  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ARMOUR
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Richard Dunne and Domonic Foley scored in the
second half Sunday as Ireland rallied for a 2-2 tie with Mexico in
the U.S. Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams blew opportunities to win in the final minutes. Irish
midfielder Kevin Kilbane's shot went just wide, and Irish
goalkeeper Dean Kiely saved a goal at the other end by punching
Joaquin Beltran's header off a corner kick into the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish play the United States on Tuesday in Boston while
Mexico takes on South Africa on Wednesday in Dallas. The Americans
beat South Africa 4-0 on Saturday in the opener of the U.S. Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from pride and bragging rights, the game had little
meaning for either team. Ireland missed out on the European
Championship and doesn't start qualifying for the World Cup until
September.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish also were playing without four of their top players,
including captain Roy Keane. Keane, who plays for Manchester
United, suffered a hamstring injury and missed United's final three
games in England's Premier League.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico essentially brought a club team. Most of the players were
from Pumas, and Pumas coach Hugo Sanchez, not national manager
Manuel Lapuente, coached the Mexicans on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the club team that dominated early, taking a 2-0 lead
in the 54th minute when Horacio Sanchez tapped in a pass from
Daniel Osorno right in front of the goal.
</P>
<P>
   After being outshot 7-3 in the first half, the Irish finally got
going in the second. In the 60th minute, Jason McAteer took a
corner kick that sailed wide, but Gary Breen headed it back toward
the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne, waiting right in front of the goal, kicked it in with the
inside of his right foot to cut Mexico's lead to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland scored again 11 minutes later on the smoothest play of
the game. McAteer passed to Stephen Carr, who dribbled downfield
toward the right side of the goal.
</P>
<P>
   When Carr was about six yards out, he sent a crossing pass to
Foley, who simply tapped the ball home, tying the game at 2 in the
71st minute.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico scored its first goal in the 38th minute. Daniel Osorno
took a pass from Luis Perez and shot from about 20 yards out. The
ball deflected off of Breen and into the right side of the net.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish had a chance to score in the 45th minute when Niall
Quinn headed McAteer's corner kick toward the net, but the ball hit
the post and bounced off.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The tournament is sponsored by Nike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
