<HEADLINE> World Cup Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Argentina and Brazil both eked out 1-0 victories
Sunday in
qualifiers for the 2002 World Cup to take the top two spots in the
South American standings.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Argentina, the world champion in 1978 and 1986, needed Gustavo
Lopez's left-footed volley from the edge of the penalty box with
seven minutes left to beat Bolivia at Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   The hosts were sluggish in the opening 45 minutes, but dominated
the second half. Minutes after the break, Claudio Lopez tested
Bolivian goalkeeper Jose Carlos Fernandez with a swerving volley.
Later, Fernandez punched away a bending shot by Roberto Sensini,
and Gabriel Batistuta's free kick hit the post.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, owner of a record four World Cup titles and runner-up to
France in 1994, got past Peru in Lima thanks to a goal by Antonio
Carlos in the 35th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos, positioned at the edge of the penalty box, took a long
pass from Cafu, chested the ball past goalkeeper Miguel Miranda,
then scored with a left-footed shot.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil striker Edmundo was ejected with four minutes left for a
rough tackle on Roberto Palacios, but Peru couldn't capitalize.
</P>
<P>
   Peru has won three of 32 games against Brazil since 1936, with
the last victory 15 years ago. The last time they met, in 1997,
Brazil won 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, Colombia beat Venezuela 3-0 at Bogota. Midfielder
Alexander Viveros made it 1-0 in the 27th minute, defender Ivan
Ramiro Cordoba doubled the lead 15 minutes later, and Ivan Rene
Valenciano finished the scoring with three minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina improved to 3-0 for nine points, two ahead of Brazil
(2-0-1) and three up on Paraguay and Uruguay (both 2-1). Bolivia
dropped to 0-2-1, Peru to 1-1-1, and Colombia is 1-0-2. Venezuela
is 0-3 and has been outscored 9-0.
</P>
<P>
   The top four teams from the continent advance to the World Cup,
while the fifth-place finisher meets the Oceania champion in a
playoff for another tournament spot.
</P>
<P>
   In the day's other 2002 qualifier, Canada beat Cuba 1-0 at
Havana in the first leg of a home-and-away playoff for a semifinal
berth in the CONCACAF region, which covers North and Central
America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Jason De Vos scored on a first-half header as Canada
extended its unbeaten streak to 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   The teams play again next Sunday in Winnipeg, with the winner of
the total-goals series advancing to a round of group play against
Mexico, Trinidad and Tobago, and Panama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
