<DOCNO> APW20000604.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Election Problems Persist  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER TOOTHAKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- The Spanish firm hired to fix the
technical problems that led to the suspension of Venezuela's
national balloting threatened to pull out of the process unless
elections are postponed until August.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Indra in Venezuela, Juan Navarro, said too many
technical problems still exist, and added that if the interim
legislature decides to hold elections in July his company ''won't
participate.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't risk our prestige, we can't deceive our client,''
said Navarro. His comments appeared in Sunday's El Nacional
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Supreme Tribunal, the country's highest court,
suspended elections because of computer problems that threatened
the vote count for the May 28 election.
</P>
<P>
   The postponement of the vote and the subsequent resignation of
the five-member National Election Council last Monday, due to
pressure from both pro-government and opposition parties, has
created an electoral crisis and calls for reforming the electoral
process.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders insisted the postponement reflected
astonishing incompetence by members of the election board, who were
hand-picked by President Hugo Chavez's political coalition -- an
exercise widely criticized as undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
   The electoral crisis comes at a critical moment for Venezuela.
Politically, the country has been in limbo since last year when
Chavez pushed through a new constitution that dissolved the
congress and called for new balloting to ''re-legitimize'' most
public offices, including the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, a former paratrooper who led a failed 1992 coup attempt,
insists he is carrying out a ''social revolution'' in Venezuela
through radical reform, but his opponents claim he represents a
threat to the democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro said additional time was needed to reorganize because of
problems with the database and the ballots that contain information
on more than 36,000 candidates running for some 6,200 offices.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the country's temporary congress appointed a new
election council who must scramble to correct last minute changes
in the database containing candidate lists, erroneous information
on ballots, and reprogram software before new balloting can occur.
</P>
<P>
   The process was intended to help restore public confidence in a
board that was plagued by accusations of incompetence and political
ties.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Francisco Arias Cardenas, Chavez's main
political rival, said Arias opposed giving the congress a role in
selecting the board members because the temporary legislature is
dominated by the president's political allies. He added, however,
Arias was willing to give the new board the benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature is expected to set a fresh election date this
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
