<HEADLINE> Russia Patriarch Eyes Pope Meeting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The head of Russia's Orthodox Church said Sunday
he didn't rule out a meeting with Pope John Paul II, but said
centuries-old disagreements between the Catholic and Orthodox
churches needed to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ''Such a meeting shouldn't happen just before the television
cameras,'' Patriarch Alexy II said during a trip to northern
Russia, according to the Interfax news agency. ''It's necessary
that it be well prepared for and bring about concrete results.''
</P>
<P>
   But Alexy said ''bleeding still continues from the wounds'' that
continue to strain relations. Among outstanding issues, he
mentioned Roman Catholic dioceses in western parts of Ukraine that
he said belong to the Orthodox fold. The dioceses switched
allegiances centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials on Saturday ruled out a visit to Russia by the
pope. There was speculation that President Vladimir Putin, who will
visit Italy next week, would ask the pope to come to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Alexei has been an outspoken supporter of a law in Russia
banning foreign religious groups from the country and has not
supported efforts to ease tensions between the Catholic and
Orthodox churches.
</P>
</TEXT>
