<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> After a decade, new hearings on Sound cleanup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Ten years ago, sewage washing up on the
shores of Long Island Sound routinely closed beaches and fish kills
devastated those making their living on the water.
</P>
<P>
   Today, millions of lobsters are dying off in a mystery
scientists are rushing to solve.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by the cleanup spurred from the outrage and ideas voiced
in public hearings on the Sound in 1990, environmental officials
are this year holding a new round of forums. The goal is to build
on the efforts that have improved the health of the Sound and
tackle problems that remain.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope the new hearings ... really put a spotlight on these
critical areas,'' said David J. Miller, executive director of the
National Audubon Society of New York State, who organized the
Listen to the Sound hearings in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Those hearings, where more than 400 people testified, led to the
creation of a Citizens' Agenda for the future of Long Island Sound
</P>
<P>
   ''It had a serious and beneficial impact on the Comprehensive
Management plan adopted by the EPA,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency Comprehensive Conservation
and Management Plan was finalized and adopted by the governors of
Connecticut and New York in 1994, along with a Long Island Sound
Restoration Agreement. The agreement committed the federal
government and the states to carry out the plan, which resulted in
the reduction of sewage and toxic pollutants in the Sound and its
surrounding marshlands.
</P>
<P>
   Annual beach cleanups have become a staple on the New York and
Connecticut shorelines. So have regular education programs. Most
schools in shoreline communities have some curriculum based on Long
Island Sound ecology, said David Galt, director of Environmental
Programs for the Long Island Soundkeeper Fund.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Connecticut Department of Environmental
Protection's sale of Sound preservation license plates has funded
183 projects in 53 towns since its inception in 1992. On May 31,
the state announced it had sold 100,000 plates, and awarded
$336,000 in grants to 22 environmental projects to benefit the
Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Galt said more needs to be done, including improvements at
sewage treatment plants in New York, which have lagged behind
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Other improvements are hard to gauge, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as all the marine life in Long Island Sound, has it
improved? Well, we've just had the lobster die-off, and it's also
affecting crabs,'' he said. ''There have been ups and downs of
specific species, but is that a natural occurrence? We don't
know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-04-00 2134 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
