<SUBHEAD>
Indonesian Earthquake Kills At Least 25
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- A powerful earthquake that lasted several minutes
and shook a wide area rocked the Indonesian island of Sumatra, leaving at least
25 dead and thousands homeless. The Indonesian Meteorological and Geophysical
Service said the quake, measuring 7.3, was centered beneath the Indian Ocean,
about 400 miles northwest of Jakarta. A magnitude 6 aftershock hit 11 minutes
afterward, and 53 smaller tremors were recorded.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Solomon Islands Premier Taken Hostage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) -- New Zealand's Ministry of Foreign Affairs and
Trade said Monday the prime minister of the Solomon Islands has been taken
hostage and armed rebels have put up road blocks in the capital of Honiara.
Ministry spokesman Brad Pattersfield said insurgents from the country's Malaita
Eagle Force militia were holding Prime Minister Bartholemew Ulufa'alua hostage.
In Canberra, Australia's Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade said armed
groups had overrun key installations in Honiara overnight in an apparent coup
attempt. The Malaita Eagle Force had seized ''key installations in Honiara
including some police stations and the Government Telecommunications Center,''
the department said.
</P>
