</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- The Spanish firm hired to fix the technical
problems that led to the suspension of Venezuela's national balloting threatened
to pull out of the process unless elections are postponed until August. The
president of Indra in Venezuela, Juan Navarro, said too many technical problems
still exist, and added that if the interim legislature decides to hold elections
in July his company ''won't participate.'' Last week, the Supreme Tribunal, the
country's highest court, suspended elections because of computer problems that
threatened the vote count for the May 28 election.
</P>
