<HEADLINE> Long Shot Wins Plate Trial Stakes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Long shot Pete's Sake went to the lead and never
looked back Sunday, winning the $168,600 Plate Trial Stakes by six
lengths at Woodbine.
</P>
<P>
   The victory made the 3-year-old son of 1993 Queen's Plate winner
Peteski a favorite for this year's 141st running of the Queen's
Plate on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   The Plate Trial has produced 22 winners of the Queen's Plate
through its 58-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Owned by Jerry Frankel, trained by New York-based Todd Pletcher
and ridden by Patrick Husbands, Pete's Sake went off at 22-1. He
assumed command of the 1[-mile race around the first turn and held
his position by keeping pace-setters For Our Sake and Volio at bay.
At the top of the stretch the Ontario-bred chestnut began drawing
clear from his nine rivals and was clocked in 1:53.05.
</P>
<P>
   I and I, the Plate winter book favorite, came from seventh to
finish second, while Bold n' Fancy was third another 7{ lengths
back.
</P>
<P>
   Strike Smartly, which went off as the 2-5 favorite, finished
fifth, 16{ lengths behind the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Pete's Sake earned $101,160 for his second career win, raising
his lifetime earnings to $129,460. He returned $46.80, $19.60 and
$13.80.
</P>
<P>
   I and I returned $11.60 and $7.60, while Bold n' Fancy was
$11.20 to show.
</P>
</TEXT>
