<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Horn of Africa Peace Talks Resume  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLAS MARMIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Ethiopia reportedly issued new demands
for international peacekeepers Sunday as it resumed indirect talks
with Eritrea to resolve a two-year border war.
</P>
<P>
   The talks included ''serious discussion'' on security issues,
including an Ethiopian army redeployment and use of international
observers and troops in the Horn of Africa, a Western diplomat said
on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia's premier said his country would withdraw from Eritrean
territory if international peacekeepers were based in lands it now
occupies, the state-owned Ethiopian Herald reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Chief negotiator Algerian Justice Minister Ahmed Ouyahia met
separately with the Eritrean and Ethiopian delegations Sunday,
after both had studied proposals put forth Saturday on the
withdrawal of both armies and the demarcation of common borders.
</P>
<P>
   Ouyahia gave the delegations until Monday to consider a second
working document, the details of which were not made public.
</P>
<P>
   ''The atmosphere is good. We are making progress,'' said U.S.
envoy Anthony Lake, but added that it was too early to predict an
outcome. Peace talks have been underway here for nearly a week.
</P>
<P>
   The violence has centered on a poorly defined border area
running 620 miles between the two African countries. Ethiopia sent
its forces into Eritrea on May 12, saying its troops would remain
until they had retaken all disputed land. Eritrea agreed last week
to retreat from lands Ethiopia had claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea claimed Sunday that it had repulsed a new offensive
launched by Ethiopia near the port of Assab on the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ''The large scale attack ... has been totally foiled, with the
Ethiopian army suffering huge losses,'' the Eritrean Foreign
Ministry said in a statement. Ethiopia's 38th Division was ''almost
decimated,'' and 3,755 Ethiopian troops ''were killed, wounded or
taken prisoner.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no independent verification of the fighting, but
Ethiopian state spokeswoman Selome Taddesse denied the claim that
Ethiopia was launching new battles.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as we are concerned, the war is over,'' Ethiopian Prime
Minister Meles Zenawi said, according to the Herald on Sunday.
Ethiopia announced Wednesday it considered the war finished, having
achieved its territorial goals.
</P>
<P>
   However, the premier added, ''the Eritrean government has
declared that the war is not yet finished, (and) we are thus
justified to take retaliatory measures to repulse any Eritrean
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenawi said Ethiopia wanted an international peacekeeping force,
as well as an agreement from Eritrea ''that it will not again
initiate war against Ethiopia'' -- demands made known to Algiers
negotiators, according to the Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia also said Sunday that an earlier framework agreement
dealing with border demarcation -- the crux of the dispute -- should
be reviewed in accordance with the existing situation on the
ground, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   That appeared to be an indication that Ethiopia could claim some
territory it had previously acknowledged as Eritrean.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier document contained proposals supported by the
Organization of African Unity, which is sponsoring the talks.
</P>
<P>
   In Algiers, the two delegations have yet to meet face-to-face in
the talks. Besides Lake, Italian Undersecretary of State Rino Seri
and an EU representative also played key roles in the discussions.
A first round of talks collapsed May 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 2212 </TRAILER>
