<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kelly, Pilot Differ on Accident  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMBURG, N.Y. (AP) -- Jim Kelly acknowledges that there have been
differing accounts of the rough landing of the plane in which he
was a passenger, and the former Buffalo Bills quarterback stands by
his initial version.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, attending a VIP party Sunday for his 14th annual Jim
Kelly Golf Tournament, responded to questions that have arisen
about what exactly happened when his plane was forced to land
shortly after departing from an Alaskan hunting trip on May 20.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know what happened, I know what I had to say,'' Kelly told
the Buffalo News. ''I know that when you get out of a plane and you
go underwater, it's a little deeper than six inches. I know I'm not
a goldfish, I know I'm not that small.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly first told Buffalo's WGRZ-TV about the incident Tuesday,
when he was quoted as saying, ''I had to swim to shore.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaskan National Traffic and Safety Board chief Jim LaBelle
issued a statement Friday citing pilot Jerry Jacques' version as
''landing in a tidal zone, in six inches of water.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Kelly, ''I think, pretty much, that the pilot had to say
that. I talked to him, and I think for his own case and the Federal
Aviation Administration, he has his own things that he had to say.
I'm just glad I took swimming lessons as a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said he's heard his share of yarns about what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ''It got so bad, I've had people coming up to me saying, 'I
heard you got your finger ripped off by a nail,''' quipped Kelly,
who said he had a fingernail torn off during the landing. ''I heard
so many stories, by that time, who knows what's going to go on?''
</P>
<P>
   One aspect Kelly did agree with the NTSB report on was minimal
damage to the plane, a Super Cub on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ''The prop was bent pretty good,'' Kelly said. ''The front end
of the plane was dented pretty good, there wasn't much damage. I
think maybe he thought because there wasn't much damage, why report
it? When he had to report it, six inches of water sounds a lot
better than 10 or 11 feet of water.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
