<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warrick Signs Deal With Bengals  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Wide receiver Peter Warrick agreed to a
seven-year contract worth $42 million on Sunday, the fastest
signing for a Cincinnati Bengals' top draft pick since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick signed the deal Sunday evening at the suburban Indian
Hill home of Bengals executive vice president Katie Blackburn, the
club confirmed on its Web site. The Bengals called a news
conference for Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, who played at Florida State, was the fourth overall
pick in the NFL draft. He'll get more than $10 million in signing
and reporting bonuses this year, agent Jim Gould said.
</P>
<P>
   The contract contains a voidable seventh year, meaning the deal
would be shortened to six years if Warrick plays 45 percent of the
downs in any season.
</P>
<P>
   If Warrick reaches all of the performance goals to kick in the
contract's various escalator clauses, he will make $42 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I'll get that,'' Warrick said. ''They're very
reachable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals have a history of holdouts by first-round draft
picks. Quarterback Akili Smith missed virtually all of training
camp last year, limiting him as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bengals planning to get rid of receiver Carl Pickens,
they needed Warrick signed before training camp so he could move
into a starter's role.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of promising things going on with the Bengals,
and we like to think that Peter's signing is now one of those
things,'' Gould said.
</P>
<P>
   Gould, who's based in Cincinnati, and agent Norm Nixon handled
the contract negotiations. Gould has represented numerous Bengals
in the past and coaches the soccer team of Blackburn's 5-year-old
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're extremely pleased to have this done and to know that
Peter will be with us on the first day of training camp,''
Blackburn said. ''I give a lot of the credit to Norm and Jim for
being willing to talk seriously and then do a deal at this point in
the year. We've found in some past negotiations with top picks that
there was a reluctance to begin serious talks until camp was upon
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-day negotiations ended at noon Sunday when Blackburn
and the agents agreed on terms.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations were the Bengals' shortest with a first-round
pick since Ohio State's Dan Wilkinson signed his seven-year, $14.4
million contract on May 5, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick is the third first-round pick to agree to a contract
this year. Cleveland Browns defensive end Courtney Brown and New
York Jets tight end Anthony Becht also have come to terms.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick won't work out with the Bengals until he completes more
of the community service sentence he received in Florida after
pleading guilty to a petty theft charge.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, a former Florida State teammate and a store clerk were
charged after the two players paid $21.40 for more than $400 worth
of clothes last Sept. 29 at a Dillard's department store in
Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   He will remain in Florida cleaning up trash along highways as
part of his 30-day sentence. His agents expect him to complete the
sentence before training camp starts July 21.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.bengals.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 2225 </TRAILER>
