<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanians Vote in Local Elections  </HEADLINE>
By ALISON MUTLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP)-- Exit polls from local elections showed
Sunday the party of former President Ion Iliescu leading in the
capital Bucharest for the first time in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The local elections, in which financial unrest and
disillusionment with politicians kept many voters away, were
considered significant as a measure of political power in advance
of parliamentary and presidential elections later this year. Polls
show Iliescu favored to defeat President Emil Constantinescu in the
presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   Final official results were not expected before Monday in the
local contests, in which Romanians chose mayors and other officials
in the 3,000 cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
   In the capital, however, exit polls announced shortly after
balloting ended showed Sorin Oprescu, 49, director of the Municipal
Hospital and a member of Iliescu's Party of Social Democracy,
leading with 44 percent in the contest for Bucharest mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Two other candidates -- Catalin Calin Chirita of the Democratic
Convention and Transport Minister Traian Basescu of the Democratic
Party -- were trailing with 17 percent each according to the poll.
Thirty-three other candidates shared the remaining 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There was no margin of error given for the poll.
</P>
<P>
   If the final results follow the exit polls, Oprescu will face
the second-highest vote getter in a runoff in two weeks since the
winner needs an absolute majority of votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   Iliescu said the result was a good omen for his left-leaning
Party of Social Democracy. His party held office in the capital
from 1990 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Some 17 million Romanians were eligible to vote. However, polls
remained open for an additional two hours in areas where the
turnout was below the 50 percent level necessary for the results to
be valid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
