<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, June 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indonesian Earthquake Kills At Least 25
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- The death toll was expected to rise after a
powerful earthquake and several strong aftershocks rocked the Indonesian island
of Sumatra. At least 25 were dead and thousands were homeless. The Indonesian
Meteorological and Geophysical Service said the quake, measuring magnitude 7.3,
was centered beneath the Indian Ocean, about 400 miles northwest of Jakarta. The
quake lasted several minutes and shook a wide area. A magnitude 6 aftershock hit
11 minutes afterward, and 53 smaller tremors were recorded.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Horn of Africa Peace Talks Resume
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Ethiopia reportedly issued new demands for
international peacekeepers Sunday as it resumed indirect talks with Eritrea to
resolve a two-year border war. The talks included ''serious discussion'' on
security issues, including an Ethiopian army redeployment and use of
international observers and troops in the Horn of Africa, a Western diplomat
said on condition of anonymity. Ethiopia's premier said his country would
withdraw from Eritrean territory if international peacekeepers were based in
lands it now occupies, the state-owned Ethiopian Herald reported Sunday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Solomon Islands Premier Taken Hostage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) -- New Zealand's Ministry of Foreign Affairs and
Trade said Monday the prime minister of the Solomon Islands has been taken
hostage and armed rebels have put up road blocks in the capital of Honiara.
Ministry spokesman Brad Pattersfield said insurgents from the country's Malaita
Eagle Force militia were holding Prime Minister Bartholemew Ulufa'alua hostage.
In Canberra, Australia's Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade said armed
groups had overrun key installations in Honiara overnight in an apparent coup
attempt. The Malaita Eagle Force had seized ''key installations in Honiara
including some police stations and the Government Telecommunications Center,''
the department said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
OAS Launches Annual Assembly
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario (AP) -- As hundreds of anti-free trade protesters chanted
outside, foreign ministers from the Organization of American States launched
their annual assembly today, expecting to focus on Peru's presidential election.
Police arrested 41 people -- 35 of whom were among 200 who mobbed a bus
containing three OAS delegates and a driver, according to Staff Sgt. Dave
Rossell of the Windsor Police Service. Protesters chanted and wagged their
fingers at the police officers, who in turn rapped nightsticks on riot shields
to move the crowd back.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Venezuela Election Problems Persist
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- The Spanish firm hired to fix the technical
problems that led to the suspension of Venezuela's national balloting threatened
to pull out of the process unless elections are postponed until August. The
president of Indra in Venezuela, Juan Navarro, said too many technical problems
still exist, and added that if the interim legislature decides to hold elections
in July his company ''won't participate.'' Last week, the Supreme Tribunal, the
country's highest court, suspended elections because of computer problems that
threatened the vote count for the May 28 election.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S.-E.U. Data Privacy Deal Near
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Despite protests from consumer rights advocates, the European
Union has endorsed a data privacy pact with the United States that critics fear
will erode legal protections many Europeans now enjoy. The so-called safe harbor
agreement, likely to take effect this summer, will make U.S. businesses
responsible for safeguarding the privacy of any personal information they may
collect about European consumers. If U.S. companies agree to comply -- the pact
is voluntary -- they would gain ''safe harbor'' from prosecution or lawsuits by
EU governments.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
'Copehagen' Named Best Play At Tonys
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ''Copenhagen'' was chosen best play and '''Kiss Me, Kate,''
best musical revival today, as Michael Blakemore scored a Tony first -- winning
the awards for his direction of both. Susan Stroman, whose musical ''Contact,''
a daring dance play that pushes musical-theater boundaries, won the award for
best choreography. Elton John and Tim Rice picked up the award for best score
for their pop retelling of ''Aida.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise In Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks surged Monday following Friday's dramatic recovery
in technology stocks on Wall Street. The Nikkei Stock Average rose 344.13 points
to 17,144.19 in early trading.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lakers Defeat Portland 89-84, Win Series
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Lakers scored 15 consecutive points in
the fourth quarter to erase a 15-point Portland lead and went on to beat the
Trail Blazers 89-84 tonight in Game 7 of the Western Conference finals. Los
Angeles advances to the NBA Finals for the first time since 1991 with Game 1 on
Wednesday against the Indiana Pacers.
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA 
</P>
</TEXT>
