<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Rebel Leader Meets Military  </HEADLINE>
By ROHAN SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- The martial law regime said Monday it was
firmly in control of Fiji, and that it had drawn the line on any
peace deal it would offer the rebel leader holding more than 30
hostages in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel boss George Speight must release the hostages and
surrender his arms to get a promised amnesty. The regime of
Commodore Frank Bainimarama would then stay in charge until law and
order were restored in Fiji, said military spokesman Lt. Col.
Filipo Tarakinikini.
</P>
<P>
   Speight and his followers will be barred from participation in
any interim government -- going against one of Speight's key demands
for ending the hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have stated that this is impossible,'' Bainimarama said
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Bainimarama said Speight cannot end up in control of Fiji ''for
one simple reason -- there's been a lot of talk of backlash'' by
locals and the overseas community.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's influential tribal chiefs could play a role in
choosing an interim civilian government, Tarakinikini told an
Australian television interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   ''The military line has been drawn, and we have told Mr. Speight
and his group that beyond this we are not going to negotiate,''
Tarakinikini said, adding that the military could stay in control
for up to three months.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was not completely at odds with Speight's proposal for
ending the crisis. He said he would accept military control to
restore law and order, but only if there was a strict time limit.
</P>
<P>
   Speight spent Sunday airing his latest demands to Fiji's
military government -- and later said that a new trust was
developing. He did not say, though, when he might free the
hostages, including deposed Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry.
</P>
<P>
   Speight said that, after nine hours of ''cordial talks,'' one
significant remaining issue was the disagreement over how Fiji will
be governed once the standoff ended.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are well on the way now that the initial barriers of
concern have been broken down,'' Speight told reporters, without
elaborating. ''We have come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Speight's earlier plan to release his captives over the weekend
collapsed Saturday, when he accused the military regime of
bargaining in bad faith.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides planned a new set of negotiations on Monday at
Bainimarama's barracks headquarters, but Speight did not shown up
by the appointed time.
</P>
<P>
   Speight has been emboldened by his confidence that the military
wouldn't try to rescue the hostages by attacking. And though many
of his goals have been accomplished -- including the scrapping of
Fiji's constitution and the removal of the president -- he presented
more demands Saturday in a nine-point proposal that would
effectively let him pick the next government.
</P>
<P>
   ''The army will never attack Fijians. Never,'' Speight told
Australia's Channel Nine television.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji's ethnic Indians control many businesses, and Speight wants
to prevent them from ever running the country again. Although
Speight claims to represent all indigenous Fijians, many have
rallied against him and expressed support for Chaudhry's
government.
</P>
<P>
   Speight also said in the interview aired Sunday that he had
offered his four female hostages freedom Saturday, but they had
preferred to stay and support their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ''We asked the ladies ... if they wished to go home today, or
sometime this weekend,'' Speight said in the interview, recorded
Saturday. ''And they chose not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on a local Fijian current affairs show, Tarakinikini
thanked Fiji's Indian community Sunday for showing patience while
the hostages were still being held.
</P>
<P>
   Chaudhry was Fiji's first prime minister of Indian descent.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are most grateful they are willing to stand by and allow
the army to bring the country to normalcy -- then we can begin a
dialogue,'' Tarakinikini said.
</P>
<P>
   Rich trading partners including the United States, Australia and
New Zealand have threatened to impose economic sanctions if Fiji,
3,620 kilometers (2,250 miles) northeast of Sydney, Australia,
doesn't return to democratic rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-04-00 2357 </TRAILER>
